<hr /></div>

<div id="main-text">

<h2 id="HistBack">1. Historical Background</h2>

<p>
It is useful to begin with a brief historical background. Science and
scientific thought have long functioned in Latin America as beacons of
civic hope and progress amidst multiple recurrent frustrations that
vary in kind and texture from place to place. In most of the region,
the Enlightenment ideals that fueled independence movements of the
early nineteenth century were quickly disappointed by the chaos and
general barbarism that followed in much of the region until the 1860s.
It was different in Brazil, where emancipation from Europe occurred
gradually and orderly during the century, but there too problems grew
as did also tensions between the economic elite and the
country&rsquo;s leading liberal thinkers.</p>

<p>
Reacting against expanding frustration, many Latin Americans saw a
solution in the &ldquo;scientific&rdquo; ways of thinking dominant in
the industrialized countries. In the 1850s a progressive philosophy
was in full flight in the larger world, ready-made for Latin American
visionaries: French Positivism, a doctrine of progress and secular
religion, centered on hope in modern science, led by Auguste Comte.
Committed to fighting the temptations of barbarism, the positivists
sought to continue the project of the Enlightenment. Against the
impulsive approach to decision-making then prevailing in most of Latin
America, local positivists sought to extend scientific thought to
philosophy and political action, convinced it would promote
objectivity, rational consensus, publicly accessible cumulative truth
in all spheres, along the material success characteristic of modern
science. Between about 1870 and 1910 positivism took strong hold in
much of Latin America, with an agenda that called for methodological
improvement in the local practice of the natural sciences, medicine,
and education, also greatly influencing activity in philosophy,
history, art, and law (see, e.g., Frondizi 1943; Zea 1943&ndash;44;
Nachman 1977; Quintanilla 2006). In Argentina, scientism and
Comte&rsquo;s philosophy had influential defenders, notably Domingo
Faustino Sarmiento, many scientists (e.g., paleontologist Florentino
Ameghino), physician-philosophers (e.g., Jos&eacute; Ingenieros and
Alejandro Korn), educators (e.g., Pedro Scalabrini), and lawyers
(e.g., Carlos Octavio Bunge, whose nephew Mario A. Bunge would become
an international figure in philosophy of science in the following
century). A conviction these thinkers shared stated that a modern and
efficient system of public education was indispensable for achieving
the desired transformations. Interest in advancing the positivist
approach grew to religious heights especially in Brazil, where it was
championed by distinguished political figures, notably Miguel de
Lemos, a reorganizer of the country&rsquo;s curriculum and a decisive
force in the construction of the first Humanity Temple for the
propagation of Comte&rsquo;s ideas in the world. When Brazil became a
republic in 1889, positivist doctrine made its way to the new flag,
the motto &ldquo;Order and Progress&rdquo; lifted from Comte&rsquo;s
writings&mdash;in <em>Syst&egrave;me de Politique Positive</em>
(1851), the preliminary discourse&rsquo;s conclusion begins with the
words &ldquo;Love for principle, order for base, and progress for
aim&rdquo; (<em>L&rsquo;amour pour principe, l&rsquo;ordre pour base,
et le progr&egrave;s pour but</em>; p. 321).</p>

<p>
The influence of positivism in Mexico was nearly as strong,
particularly in education, as exemplified by the labors of the
respected chemist and medical doctor Gabino Barreda, who banned
religion and traditional philosophy from the school curriculum and
centralized access to higher education and culture. In Chile, the
brothers Jorge and Enrique Lagarrigue were two leading advocates of
Comte&rsquo;s philosophy and his Humanity Religion. In Colombia,
Rafael Nu&ntilde;ez, an educational reformer and three times president
of Colombia, actively promoted positivism, as did in Peru (with
touches of Herbert Spencer&rsquo;s evolutionism) such figures as
Javier Prado, Manuel Gonz&aacute;lez Prada, Celso Bambar&eacute;n, and
Manuel Vicente Villar&aacute;n. In Bolivia, positivism also had
influential defenders from the 1870s through the 1890s, notably a
circle of writers, &ldquo;<em>C&iacute;rculo Literario</em>&rdquo;, in
whose journal works by Charles Darwin, Luis Dumont, Ernst H. P. A.
Haeckel and other naturalists appeared in translation.</p>

<p>
With all this intellectual and progressive enthusiasm in the air,
hopes of imminent general improvement ran high, but
&ldquo;positive&rdquo; results were slow in coming. The expectations
of economic advancement and civic improvement did not materialize as
advertised. To compound matters, the devastation caused by the Great
War in Europe badly compromised social faith in the products of
science. Positivism waned accordingly in Latin America, replaced in
the 1920s by a more radical social thought, especially Marxism, as
well as approaches distrustful of naturalist reasoning (Bergsonian
spiritualism, phenomenology, and later existentialism). Metaphysics
unbridled by standard logic became dominant in many university
circles.</p>

<p>
Reactions to excessively &ldquo;high philosophy&rdquo; began to arise
in the 1940s, helped by the arrival of thinkers from Europe, for
example Juan David Garc&iacute;a Bacca in the cases of Ecuador,
Mexico, and Venezuela, Hans Lindemann in Argentina, and Gilles-Gaston
Granger in Brazil. Along the way came a revival of interest in logic,
science-friendly epistemology, and the study of conceptual structures.
Thanks to these developments, when philosophy of science became a
professional field in the late 1940s, Latin America had some
scientists and philosophers ready and willing to fully join their
counterparts in Europe and North America. Since then, for the past
seventy years, a number of philosophers of science based in Latin
America, often in uncooperative environments, have managed to produce
work of the highest international standards (something not so clearly
apparent in the developing world in other branches of international
philosophy).</p>

<p>
By the mid 1990s, academic centers in Latin America began to benefit
from the kind of world-wide interaction made possible by the Internet,
electronic libraries, and improved forms of institutional support for
integration and travel. With geographical and institutional barriers
greatly reduced, the field expanded considerably. Over the last three
decades virtually every theme in philosophy of science would develop a
presence in works produced in Latin America. Dialogue and
collaboration between researchers now transcend the traditional local
boundaries. This new global environment makes less relevant the
traditional geographical approach to philosophical production in the
region. Accordingly, Sections 3 and 4, devoted to activity from the
mid 1990s on, structure the subject around themes, concepts, and
principles (rather than around geography and individuals).</p>

<h2 id="EarlDeca">2. The Early Decades</h2>

<h3 id="Mexi">2.1 Mexico</h3>

<p>
Philosophy of science developed a robust presence at Universidad
Nacional Aut&oacute;noma de M&eacute;xico (UNAM), a major institution
at the forefront of intellectual life in the country and the
Spanish-speaking world. The discipline began to be cultivated in the
1950s at UNAM&rsquo;s School of Philosophy and Literature
(<em>Facultad de Filosof&iacute;a y Letras,</em> FFyL), with faculty
members such as Eli de Gortari, founder (in 1955) of the Seminar on
Scientific and Philosophical Problems &ndash; active to the present
day &ndash; in which distinguished scientists and philosophers have
participated through its different stages. Also important was the
teaching work of Wonfilio Trejo in the epistemology of empirical
science and of Hugo Padilla, a pioneer in Mexico of the philosophy of
technology and translator into Spanish of central texts by G.
Frege.</p>

<p>
The discipline gained strength in the 1960s and early 1970s through
the efforts of prominent faculty members, especially Fernando
Salmer&oacute;n, Luis Villoro, and Alejandro Rossi, who encouraged
rigor and clarity in philosophy and provided scholarship support to
enable students to do post-graduate work in Europe, the United
Kingdom, and the United States. Together, they founded the journal
<em>Cr&iacute;tica</em> in 1967, a choice venue for philosophy in
Latin America and Spain. An influential work by Salmer&oacute;n,
<em>La Filosof&iacute;a y las Matem&aacute;ticas</em>, came out the
following year. Major international seminars and meetings became a
regular feature at UNAM&rsquo;s Institute for Philosophical
Investigations (<em>Instituto de Investigaciones
Filos&oacute;ficas</em>&mdash;IIF). One of the first international
seminars focused on the philosophy and history of science, which took
place in 1976, was organized by Mario Bunge (Argentina and Canada),
who carried out a productive two-year research stay at the IIF.</p>

<p>
In the 1970s, two researchers, who were fundamental in the development
of the discipline, joined the IIF: Ulises Moulines (born in
Venezuela), who moved to IIF from Munich, and Mario Otero (Uruguay),
exiled for political reasons, specialist in the history and philosophy
of mathematics, as well as in the analysis of research policies in
science and technology. During his tenure in Mexico, from 1976 to
1983, Moulines published <em>Exploraciones metacient&iacute;ficas</em>
(1982), which was the main vehicle for introducing to Latin America
the structuralist conception of scientific theories (developed by J.D.
Sneed, W. Stegm&uuml;ller, and Moulines himself). He devoted much of
his research during the 1970s and 1980s to the dynamics of theories,
applying, in an original synthesis, the formal resources of diachronic
structuralist reconstruction and Kuhnian analysis of theory change,
which is reflected in his model for the evolutionary reconstruction of
scientific theories. Another of Moulines&rsquo;s major contributions
has been his defense of a broad-spectrum pluralism (ontological,
semantic, epistemological, and methodological).</p>

<p>
Research seminars at IIF continued to develop and strengthen in the
1980s with a series of annual international symposia of philosophy.
This period was also marked by institutional investment in specialized
research libraries and the reinforcement of publishing programs at
UNAM and other institutions in Mexico. Significant papers and
monographs began to flow regularly from seminars on general philosophy
of science, philosophy of physics, and philosophy of biology. From the
mid-1980s to the present day, the IIF has continuously hosted seminars
and short courses taught by distinguished philosophers of science: Bas
van Fraassen, Dudley Shapere, Wesley Salmon, Hilary Putnam, Ricardo
G&oacute;mez, Zeljko Loparic, Marcelo Dascal, Miguel &Aacute;ngel
Quintanilla, Dorothy Edgington, Javier Echeverr&iacute;a, Larry
Laudan, Samir Okasha, Eduardo Flichman, William Wimsatt, Elliot Sober,
Oscar Nudler, Fernando Broncano, Ilkka Niiniluoto, Paul Thagard, Ian
Hacking, Helen Longino, among many others.</p>

<p>
It is important to emphasize that the consolidation and
professionalization of the philosophy of science in Mexico was
achieved mainly through the creation of specialized degree programs.
The first was at the Metropolitan Autonomous University (UAM), and the
second was at UNAM. Fernando Salmer&oacute;n and Luis Villoro, aware
of the need to train academics specialized in logic and philosophy of
science, created the first <em>Maestr&iacute;a en Filosof&iacute;a de
la Ciencia</em> in the country, at the UAM (Iztapalapa campus). At
that juncture, Le&oacute;n Oliv&eacute; returned to Mexico
&ndash; having obtained a Ph.D. at the University of Oxford &ndash; and
started this degree program in 1980, with the support of IIF
researchers, such as Ulises Moulines, Mario Otero, Elia Nathan
(history of science), Ra&uacute;l Orayen (philosophy of logic), plus
other faculty members such as Villoro himself (theory of knowledge),
Susana Berestovoy and Ignacio Jan&eacute; (logic and model theory). In
this master&rsquo; degree, the first two generations of philosophers
of science were trained, whose graduates joined the faculty of the UAM
itself, the UNAM, and other national universities. Among other
graduates are Jos&eacute; Alfredo Amor, Leobardo Plata, Fernanda
Clavel, Ana Rosa P&eacute;rez Ransanz, Ambrosio Velasco G&oacute;mez,
Ra&uacute;l Alcal&aacute;, Mario Casanueva, Carlos L&oacute;pez
Beltr&aacute;n, Jos&eacute; de Teresa and Armando C&iacute;ntora.
Despite the success of this specialized degree program, due to
institutional policy issues, the UAM-Iztapalapa modified its
philosophy curricula, and unfortunately a good part of the academics
who supported this master&rsquo;s degree &ndash; between 1980 and
1984 &ndash; abandoned the program.</p>

<p>
In the mid-1980s, Salmer&oacute;n and Villoro, together with
Oliv&eacute; &ndash; who in 1985 was appointed director of the
IIF &ndash; promoted a new scholarship program abroad in central areas
of philosophy. In this context, Ambrosio Velasco (Minnesota), Atocha
Aliseda (Stanford), Carlos L&oacute;pez Beltr&aacute;n (London), and
Raymundo Morado (Indiana) obtained their Ph.D. In parallel, the IIF
provided strong support to the UNAM&rsquo;s <em>Doctorado en
Filosof&iacute;a</em> to have high-level visiting professors such as
those mentioned above (van Fraassen, Shapere, Quintanilla, Laudan,
Echeverr&iacute;a). Furthermore, in those years, Adolfo Garc&iacute;a
de la Sienra, with a dissertation in philosophy of economics (Stanford
University), and Sergio Mart&iacute;nez, in philosophy of physics
(Indiana University), joined the IIF.</p>

<p>
Thanks to this academic policy, it was possible to gather the
necessary critical mass to create at UNAM, under the guidance of
Oliv&eacute;, the <em>Programa de Maestr&iacute;a y Doctorado en
Filosof&iacute;a de la Ciencia</em>, which started in 1993 under the
successful coordination of Ambrosio Velasco. This is the program where
most of the new generations now working in the discipline in Mexico
have been trained.</p>

<h3 id="Braz">2.2 Brazil</h3>

<p>
An influential textbook by Gilles-Gaston Granger, <em>L&oacute;gica e
Filosofia das Ci&ecirc;ncias</em> &mdash;first published in
1955&mdash;is acknowledged as the first introduction to the field in
Portuguese. A disciple of Gaston Bachelard, Granger taught at the
University of S&atilde;o Paulo (USP) from 1947 to 1953 and was a major
force in the development of philosophy of science in Brazil. His work
favored a historically-oriented approach hospitable to the Anglo-Saxon
analytic style. Back in Europe he associated himself with various
philosophical and social projects; in 1986 he was elected to the Chair
of Comparative Epistemology at the <em>Coll&egrave;ge de France</em>.
The research projects Granger started in Brazil continued after his
tenure, especially thanks to the efforts of Oswaldo Porchat.</p>

<p>
In 1964 a military coup led to government action eradicating academics
suspected of leftist sympathies, seriously disrupting many fields,
including philosophy of science. Nevertheless, faculty groups were
soon able to restore activity. In 1970, at USP Jo&atilde;o Paulo
Monteiro managed to start <em>Ci&ecirc;ncia e Filosofia</em>, a
journal dedicated to logic and philosophy of science from a plurality
of perspectives. Revitalization of the discipline continued throughout
the decade with timely research projects, often carried out in
conjunction with international visits and courses, notably ones
organized by Porchat, first at USP and after 1975 at State University
of Campinas (UNICAMP), where he headed a new unit, <em>Centro de
L&oacute;gica, Epistemologia e Hist&oacute;ria da Ci&ecirc;ncia</em>
(CLE), whose members included Zeljko Loparic and other distinguished
scholars. In 1977 CLE launched the prestigious journal
<em>Manuscrito</em>, supplemented in 1980 by <em>Cadernos de Filosofia
e Hist&oacute;ria da Ci&ecirc;ncia</em>, and in 1987 by a book series
(<em>Cole&ccedil;&atilde;o CLE</em>). CLE quickly became a symbol of
hope for philosophers and historians of science as well as logicians.
In particular, CLE is involved in the articulation of
&ldquo;Paraconsistent Logic&rdquo;, a field Newton C. da Costa began
to develop in the late 1950s and early 1960s when he was working at
Federal University of Paran&aacute;. Da Costa is one of the most
charismatic and energetic thinkers in Latin America, a world-class
figure in mathematics, logic, and philosophy of science, with a widely
recognized reputation for original works on non-classical logics, the
axiomatization of scientific theories, and structuralist philosophy of
science, orientations that continue to be active in Brazil with such
figures as Itala D&rsquo;Ottaviano and Walter Carnielli.</p>

<p>
In philosophy of science CLE supports significant research on the
character and structure of modern science as well as its concepts and
theories&mdash;conducted from a variety of perspectives, including
investigations in science teaching and the uses of philosophy of
science in education. Critical dialogue has been fostered through
seminars, distinguished international visits, research funding,
faculty and student exchanges, interdisciplinary studies, and the
publication of monographs and papers by Brazilian authors as well as
translations of major works into Portuguese. Post-graduate studies and
postdoctoral fellowships in logic and philosophy of science are
thriving accordingly at UNICAMP. One scheme developed by CLE to
attract promising faculty recently graduated from institutions
worldwide produced excellent results. In the 1980s Michel Ghins and
Harvey Brown energized analytic activity on space-time physics. Steven
French did likewise in advancing the model-theoretic approach and the
metaphysics of quantum mechanics at Campinas. With the help of these
and other recruits, philosophy of physics, mathematics, and formal
approaches to the philosophy of science thrived. At Campinas, French
and da Costa started a long-lasting collaboration that proved
remarkably fertile, resulting in influential contributions to current
debates on the metaphysics of quantum mechanics, structuralism, and
the semantic approach to theories, as well as a fresher way of looking
at the concept of truth (&ldquo;pragmatic truth&rdquo; and
&ldquo;partial truth&rdquo;). These collaborations led to many papers
(Da Costa and French 1989, 1990, 1991, 1993) as well as a book in
2003, <em>Science and Partial Truth: A Unitary Approach to Models and
Scientific Reasoning</em>, which received international acclaim for
the light it casts on philosophical logic, structuralism, and realism.
Brown and French made Brazil their country, and it is easy to imagine
how different the geography of philosophy of physics and mathematics
might have turned out had circumstances in Brazil been a little kinder
to academic life in the 1980s. Together with da Costa, the
international recruits and the local talents they began to nurture
would have probably turned CLE and USP (where Ot&aacute;vio Bueno had
worked with da Costa) into top centers for philosophy of science in
the world. Destiny dictated otherwise, however; Ghins left to a
professorship at Louvain-la-Neuve, Belgium; Brown moved to a
distinguished career at Oxford, where he was professor of the
philosophy of physics until his retirement; and French went to the
United States and then back to England where he was Editor-in-Chief of
<em>The British Journal for the Philosophy of Science</em> and is now
professor of philosophy of science (emeritus) at the University of
Leeds. Brown and French have each served terms as presidents of the
prestigious British Society for the Philosophy of Science. Happily,
all these international old members maintain productive ties with
Brazilian groups. CLE has continued to prosper over the last two
decades.</p>

<p>
Philosophical activity has expanded in Brazil at many other
institutions since the 1990s, as described in the following
sections.</p>

<h3 id="AndeCoun">2.3 Andean Countries</h3>

<p>
As with the previous countries, the field developed a presence in the
Andean countries in the early days of professional philosophy of
science.</p>

<p>
In Venezuela, Juan David Garc&iacute;a Bacca, a critic of Francisco
Franco, was forced to leave Spain and arrived in Caracas in 1946 after
periods in Ecuador and Mexico. He led a productive career at the
Faculty of Letters and Philosophy, Central University (<em>Universidad
Central de Venezuela</em>, UCV). In the mid-1930s, after completing a
doctoral dissertation on the logico-genetic structure of the physical
sciences, Garc&iacute;a Bacca joined the Vienna Circle. In Latin
America he became a prolific writer, his works including
<em>Teor&iacute;a de la relatividad</em> (1941), <em>La
f&iacute;sica</em> (1962), <em>Historia filos&oacute;fica de la
ciencia</em> (1963), <em>Teor&iacute;a y metateor&iacute;a de la
ciencia</em>, Vol. I (1977) and Vol II (1984). He remained a major
force in Caracas until 1971. In the 1970s and 1980s, Andr&eacute;s
Kalnay led a small group interested in the foundations of quantum
mechanics, first at UCV&rsquo;s School of Physics and then at
Venezuela&rsquo;s leading center for scientific research,
<em>Instituto Venezolano de Investigaciones Cient&iacute;ficas</em>.
Presently UCV runs a master&rsquo;s program in logic and philosophy of
science coordinated by Franklin Galindo.</p>

<p>
Philosophy of science in Colombia has long-enduring ties with
Continental European schools, but analytic philosophy of science has
not been absent. Already in the 1950s Mario Laserna at <em>Universidad
de los Andes</em> (Uniandes), Bogot&aacute;, promoted the study of
logic and the scientific philosophy of Hans Reichenbach. Subsequently,
local groups, helped by international visitors, have played a
consistent role in the country, notably Gonzalo Mun&eacute;var, a
Colombian philosopher of science now based in the United States, who
visits regularly his country.</p>

<p>
Activity in Peru started early in the 1950s, as attested by gatherings
organized at <em>Universidad Nacional Mayor de San Marcos</em> (UNMSM,
Peru&rsquo;s oldest university) and <em>Sociedad Peruana de
Filosof&iacute;a</em>, both in Lima. Broad interest is also reflected
in articles published in the 1950s and 1960s in the weekly literary
supplement of &ldquo;<em>El Comercio</em>&rdquo; by Oscar
Mir&oacute;-Quesada, Francisco Mir&oacute;-Quesada, and other
intellectuals interested in logic, science, and mathematics. Francisco
Mir&oacute;-Quesada, the country&rsquo;s leading philosopher, was one
of the pioneers in the development of modern philosophical logic and
science studies in Latin America, where he has indefatigably
encouraged hope in the power of human reason. Mir&oacute;-Quesada
taught at UNMSM for more than two decades, and then at <em>Universidad
Cayetano Heredia</em> (UPCH) and other centers in the country. He also
headed institutes for philosophical research, first at <em>Universidad
de Lima</em> and subsequently at <em>Universidad Ricardo Palma</em>.
Mir&oacute;-Quesada was the author of numerous works in the area of
philosophy of science, including a book in the philosophy of
mathematics, <em>Filosof&iacute;a de las Matem&aacute;ticas</em>
(1954). He has also been a champion of research in logic in the region
(it was Mir&oacute;-Quesada who suggested to name Newton da
Costa&rsquo;s approach &ldquo;paraconsistent logic&rdquo;, which he
helped to promote). Mir&oacute;-Quesada&rsquo;s most heartfelt project
focused on the study of human reason, regarded as the capacity to
reach truth, broadly understood, as outlined in his preliminary book
<em>Apuntes para una Teor&iacute;a de la Raz&oacute;n</em> (1962),
followed in 2013 by <em>Esquema de una Teor&iacute;a de la
Raz&oacute;n</em>, in which Mir&oacute;-Quesada discusses the pursuit
of rational validity in logic, science, metaphysics, and ethical
theory. In the early 1970s, young faculty trained in Europe and the
United States expanded and updated the philosophical study of science
in the country, particularly at UNMSM. Timely contributions were made,
especially by Luis Piscoya (philosophy of psychology and general
philosophy of science), Juan Abugattas (philosophy of science),
Julio-Cesar Sanz-Elguera (philosophy of science), and David Sobrevilla
(philosophy of the social sciences). Ever since, at San Marcos,
Lu&iacute;s Piscoya has been working on the interface between
philosophy of science and education; he is the author of
<em>Investigaci&oacute;n Cient&iacute;fica y Educacional: un Enfoque
Epistemol&oacute;gico</em> (1995), and numerous papers (e.g., Piscoya,
1993). In the late 1970s, an innovative program in philosophy opened
at UPCH, one of the leading research universities in the subcontinent.
Under Francisco Mir&oacute;-Quesada, many international workshops,
seminars, and courses took place in Lima as part of this venture. From
the late 1980s on, activity at UPCH continued through a program named
&ldquo;Scientific Thought&rdquo;, headed by Alberto Cordero, with the
collaboration of Sandro D&rsquo;Onofrio and other faculty members.</p>

<p>
In Chile, meanwhile, Gerold Stahl, Nathan Stemmer, and Augusto
Pescador made logic a major field in Chile in the 1960s. Later in the
decade, Roberto Torretti published a seminal book, <em>Manuel Kant.
Estudio sobre los Fundamentos de la Filosof&iacute;a
Cr&iacute;tica</em> (1967; revised edition 2005). His subsequent work
on Kant led him to wider research on the philosophical history of
science, a field that had a growing audience, especially in Santiago.
However, life in Chile became increasingly challenging as the decade
progressed. In 1970 Torretti left to Puerto Rico, where he continued
to develop his philosophical work, especially on nineteenth-century
geometry and the theory of relativity. In 1973 a ruthless military
dictatorship took over the government. It was a difficult time for
academia; Chile&rsquo;s leading journal, <em>Revista de
Filosof&iacute;a</em>, ceased publication and remained dormant until
1977. Although the institutional environment suffered greatly at most
centers, quality research continued in logic, as evidenced by
internationally acclaimed contributions during the period by Rolando
Chuaqui and others.</p>

<p>
Nearly always based in Latin American centers (Chile and Puerto Rico),
Torretti is an icon of rigor and philosophical sense and an author of
world-class level contributions; his writings are celebrated for his
insightful commentaries and educated perspectives on the rational
development of ideas, especially in Galileo, Newton, Leibniz, Kant,
nineteenth-century mathematics, Helmholtz, Poincar&eacute;, and
Einstein. Torretti&rsquo;s major publications on these subjects have a
secure place on the reading lists of leading seminars in philosophy of
science anywhere, in particular <em>Philosophy of Geometry from
Riemann to Poincar&eacute;</em> (1978), <em>Relativity and
Geometry</em> (1985), <em>Creative Understanding: Philosophical
Reflections on Physics</em> (1990), and <em>The Philosophy of
Physics</em> (1999), each an authoritative work in the philosophy and
the philosophical history of science. In the years that Torretti spent
at the Rio Piedras Campus of <em>Universidad de Puerto Rico</em>, he
led a fruitful career until his retirement in 1995. During most of
this period he was the editor of <em>Di&aacute;logos</em>, one of the
leading philosophy journals in Latin America. Cristian Soto (2023a)
provides the most comprehensive analysis of Torretti&rsquo;s views in
general philosophy of science, encompassing his nominalism in
philosophy of mathematics, his Kantian views on objectivity, his
elaboration of the creative understanding thesis, and his
understanding of HPS&rsquo; contribution to knowledge. A book-length
celebration of Roberto Torretti&rsquo;s place in the philosophy of
science was published under the title <em>Current Debates in
Philosophy of Science: In Honor of Roberto Torretti</em> (Soto 2023b)
with contributions by a broad range of Latin American scholars
(including Pablo Acu&ntilde;a, Jonas Arenhart, Alejandro Cassini, Aldo
Filomeno, Sebastian Fortin, and Olimpia Lombardi), and leading
philosophers from around the world.</p>

<h3 id="ArgeUrug">2.4 Argentina and Uruguay</h3>

<p>
On the eastern side of the southern cone, developments of considerable
international impact took place in Argentina between the 1940s and
1970s. The arrival of Hans Lindemann in the 1940s marked a turning
point in analytic philosophy in Argentina where his discussions of the
philosophy of Bertrand Russell and the Vienna Circle (he had studied
under Moritz Schlick and been a member of the Circle) encouraged
further activity, in particular research seminars and courses by Mario
Bunge, Gregorio Klimovsky, and Julio Rey Pastor. Throughout the 1950s,
the Buenos Aires area enjoyed a decade of optimism about the academic
and cultural possibilities of philosophy of science and its
applications. Several centers prospered, particularly two that were
founded in 1952. In one of them, <em>Instituto Libre de Estudios
Superiores</em>, Klimovsky and Rolando Garc&iacute;a discussed the
&ldquo;logical empiricist&rdquo; approach and gave courses that
systematically presented the new philosophy to wider audiences. The
other center was <em>C&iacute;rculo Filos&oacute;fico</em>, led by
Bunge, where his book <em>Causalidad</em> (1959a) and other works of
the period took shape, and their central materials were presented in
lectures and discussions. Bunge and Klimovsky managed to secure chairs
at <em>Universidad de Buenos Aires</em> (UBA) in philosophy of science
and logic, respectively. In the mid-1950s, their research and courses
turned the university into a world-class place in the field.
Bunge&rsquo;s administrative and cultural efforts during this period
put a strong emphasis on making professional philosophical activity
possible in Argentina. A new association for logic and scientific
philosophy, <em>Agrupaci&oacute;n Rioplatense de L&oacute;gica y
Filosof&iacute;a Cient&iacute;fica</em>, was founded in 1956, aimed at
drawing together thinkers from Argentina and Uruguay who wanted to
study philosophy in the rational and rigorous style of the new
approach, with Bunge, Klimovsky, Jorge Bosch, Gino Germani, and
Rolando Garcia among its members. A consistent group began to form,
resulting in such achievements as <em>Cuadernos de
Epistemolog&iacute;a</em>, a series that gave the whole of Latin
America and Spain access to key works in the field translated into
Spanish.</p>

<p>
In <em>Causalidad</em>, Bunge (1959a) focused on the empiricist
conception of causality and its shortcomings, blaming the empiricist
outlook for having created unnecessary confusion and pessimism in
philosophy. In this work Bunge distinguishes causal determination from
other forms of determination (structural, teleological, dialectical,
and statistical), telling apart three different senses in which the
term &ldquo;causality&rdquo; enters scientific discourse&mdash;as a
law stating that same causes produce same effects, as a relation
between cause and effect, and as a principle stating that everything
has a cause. The book came out in 1959, gaining considerable
international reception, especially due to the realist conception it
articulates. <em>Causality</em> also marks a turning point: philosophy
books one may call &ldquo;classics&rdquo; were now coming out of Latin
America and finding a place in mainstream reading lists in the
English-speaking world and Europe. A citizen of the world, perhaps the
most universalist of philosophers in the subcontinent, Bunge is
nonetheless very South American (it is hard to imagine him growing up
anywhere else but in cosmopolitan Argentina). Bunge has always been a
socially engaged intellectual, a trend already present in his efforts
as founder and secretary general of a college for workers,
<em>Universidad Obrera Argentina</em>, from 1938 until 1943. He has
remained a spirited spokesman for the need to maintain in Latin
America cultural and educational institutions capable of promoting the
practice of philosophy by minds free from ideological pressure,
financial oppression, and political or governmental control. First in
Argentina and then elsewhere, Bunge has been at &ldquo;war&rdquo;
against, as he puts it, the kind of uncritical understanding of
philosophy he found prevailing at the Faculty of Philosophy and
Letters when he joined in the 1950s, laboring to inspire a lasting
sense of professional rigor in his students and collaborators. The
series he launched, <em>Cuadernos de Epistemolog&iacute;a</em>, had a
substantial impact on scientists, philosophers, and the educated
public in the Spanish-speaking world. Bunge&rsquo;s production during
these years was remarkable; apart from <em>Causality</em>, other works
of relevance are Bunge (1959b, 1960, 1961a, 1961b, 1962a, and 1962b).
Unfortunately, these accomplishments were not achieved without
friction with colleagues and groups sympathetic to alternative ideas
Bunge could not respect. In addition, the country&rsquo;s political
and economic conditions were deteriorating. Early in the 1960s,
internal fractions within the Argentine army began to make civic life
increasingly difficult. Bunge left the country in 1963, first to the
United States (where the Vietnam War and other political developments
made him uncomfortable), then moving in 1966 to McGill University,
Montreal, where he remains until his death.</p>

<p>
Few thinkers associated with analytic philosophy strive to produce a
comprehensive philosophical system. Bunge is one of them, a thinker
trying to integrate ontology, metaphysics, epistemology, semantics,
psychology, and science coherently and fruitfully. Thus far
Bunge&rsquo;s publications make more than fifty books and hundreds of
philosophical and scientific articles, mostly in English and Spanish;
his main works were also translated into German, Italian, Russian,
French, Hungarian, and Portuguese among other languages. His works of
greatest impact in mainstream philosophy of science are arguably
<em>Causality</em> (1959a), <em>The Myth of Simplicity</em> (1963),
and <em>Foundations of Physics</em> (1967). Bunge&rsquo;s search for a
naturalist vision worth having was given systematic expression in his
<em>Treatise on Basic Philosophy</em> (an eight-volume work published
between 1974 and 1989). More recent publications by Bunge include
<em>Emergence and Convergence: Qualitative Novelty and the Unity of
Knowledge</em> (2003), <em>Chasing Reality: Strife over Realism</em>
(2006), and <em>Medical Philosophy: Conceptual Issues in Medicine</em>
(2013), as well as his much-awaited autobiography <em>Memorias entre
Dos Mundos</em> (2014), to mention a fraction of his abundant
production.</p>

<p>
In his oral presentations and seminars, Bunge pays forceful and
particular attention to the evaluation of the arguments at hand,
championing the use of logic as an expediter of clarity of thought. He
is renowned for his scathing critiques of positions that demean
reason, the search for truth, and the universality of science,
scientific naturalism, as well as positions that fail to respect human
beings as individuals. Bunge enthusiastically endorses the way in
which the Enlightenment tried to disseminate conceptual and moral
tools to revise and improve human thought and life in general.
Bunge&rsquo;s works steadily emphasize the idea that science can lead
(and has often led) to what he regards as the only sensible foundation
for social and political action: relevant knowledge of the world.
Importantly, early on in Latin America Bunge played the role of a
much-needed exemplar, a leading thinker who in the 1960s became a
&ldquo;possibility proof&rdquo; that philosophers working in the
subcontinent could, despite the often bizarre difficulties academics
face, stand up and join the philosophical conversation at the highest
levels. No Latin American philosopher had achieved anything comparable
before in cosmopolitan philosophy.</p>

<p>
Losing Bunge was a major blow, one of many as the decade unfolded.
When the military intervened the universities in 1966, many of the
most talented minds in science and the humanities fled the country.
Klimovsky remained, however, and his presence helped keep the
discipline active during this difficult period, first at UBA and then
at Belgrano University from the late 1970s until his death. Philosophy
of science did not stop in Argentina, young talent continuing to
arise, notably Alberto Coffa, at Universidad de la Plata until he too
left to the United States. The surrounding turmoil was a negative
factor, yet a remarkable period of expansion began at the end of the
decade, marked by the foundation of the <em>Sociedad Argentina de
An&aacute;lisis Filosofico</em> (SADAF), a model institution supported
by its own members, in which fellows and invited international guests
meet around topics of philosophical interest, including many of
central importance in philosophy of science. A major journal saw the
light in Buenos Aires in 1975: <em>Revista Latinoamericana de
Filosof&iacute;a</em>, followed in 1981 by another important
periodical, <em>An&aacute;lisis Filos&oacute;fico</em>.</p>

<p>
Activity in philosophy of science has grown in the country since then,
as the remaining sections of this article describe.</p>

<h2 id="GenePhilScie">3. General Philosophy of Science</h2>

<p>
Spanish-language readers interested in the philosophy of science in
Ibero-America (Latin America and Spain) are encouraged to read the
article by Alfredo Marcos and Ana Rosa Ransanz (2015), included in the
volume <em>Filosof&iacute;a Iberoamericana del Siglo XX.
Filosof&iacute;a Te&oacute;rica e Historia de la
Filosof&iacute;a</em>, belonging to the <em>Enciclopedia
Iberoamericana de Filosof&iacute;a</em>.</p>

<h3 id="ScieMeth">3.1 Scientific Method</h3>

<p>
Although Gregorio Klimovsky was one of the founding fathers of the
philosophy of science in Argentina, he was still active until the
first decade of the twenty-first century. He introduced mathematical
logic and axiomatic set theory in Argentinian universities and
defended a hypothetico-deductive method close to that of Popper, not
only for natural sciences but also for social sciences. At the turn of
the century, he published three books in Spanish, which were very
relevant in university education (Klimovsky 1994; Klimovsky and
Hidalgo 1998; Klimovsky and Boido 2005). Moreover, his autobiography
(2008) presents a vivid portrayal of the inception of analytic
philosophy of science in Argentina. But perhaps the most important
merit of Klimovsky was having been the teacher of several generations
of Argentine logicians and philosophers of science such as
Tom&aacute;s Moro Simpson, Ra&uacute;l Orayen, and Alberto Coffa.</p>

<p>
The interest in Popper&rsquo;s theses reappears in the work of Carlos
Verdugo (2009). In turn, Ambrosio Velasco G&oacute;mez (2023) focuses
on Popper&rsquo;s concepts of tradition and situational analysis. By
contrast, Alejandro Cassini (2003, in Spanish) argues for the
advantages of the Bayesian theory of confirmation over the
hypothetico-deductive method.</p>

<p>
The semantic approach to the concept of scientific theory was studied
by Ana Rosa P&eacute;rez Ransanz (1985), who compared van
Fraassen&rsquo;s proposal with that of the structuralist school; that
work, originally published in Spanish and English, was immediately
commented by van Fraassen (1985) in an article published in the same
journal. The comparison between the semantic view and the
structuralist view was revisited several years later by Germ&aacute;n
Guerrero Pino (2008, 2010, in Spanish). In turn, Juan Manuel Jaramillo
Uribe (2009, 2014, in Spanish) built a bridge between metatheoretical
structuralism with other philosophical schools, such as French
structuralism and structural realism. Pablo Lorenzano has also
developed a sustained work in the field of metatheoretical
structuralism (Balzer and Lorenzano 2000; Lorenzano and D&iacute;ez
2002, in Spanish; Lorenzano 2013), particularly applied to biology,
leading a research group with young members of different Latin
American countries.</p>

<p>
From a pragmatist perspective, P&eacute;rez Ransanz and Cristina Di
Gregori (2012) analyze the complex and multifaceted nature of human
creativity in science and in art, arguing that the mystery that still
surrounds the creativity phenomenon arises largely from a poor
understanding of the nature of experience, especially of emotional
experience.</p>

<h3 id="RatiTheoChoi">3.2 Rationality and Theory Choice</h3>

<p>
We noted that Francisco Mir&oacute;-Quesada&rsquo;s most heartfelt
project focused on the study of human reason, regarded as the capacity
to reach truth in logic, science, metaphysics, and ethical theory
(1962, 2013, in Spanish). In turn, from a perspective that defends
rationality against the attacks of postmodern thought, Ricardo
G&oacute;mez (2003, in Spanish) develops a strong criticism to
Rorty&rsquo;s arguments. A very radical position is adopted by Gonzalo
Mun&eacute;var (1981) who considers the rationality of science a
social property that should be understood in terms of biological
performance.</p>

<p>
In Mexico the interest in the rationality of science led to the
publication of two relevant volumes in Spanish on the subject, one
compiled by Ambrosio Velasco G&oacute;mez (1997) and the other by Ana
Rosa P&eacute;rez Ransanz and Velasco G&oacute;mez (2011); the second
contains more than 40 contributions of Iberoamerican authors and
offers a wide picture of the discussion on the matter in the region.
Velasco G&oacute;mez also discusses the relationship between
rationality and the method of science and proposes a new concept of
rationality (2015a), common to science and art, based on the
dialectical tension between creative innovation and consensus (2012).
In turn, Sergio Mart&iacute;nez (2003, in Spanish) focuses on the
relationship between rationality and scientific practices.</p>

<p>
More recently, problems of the empirical equivalence between theories
and the underdetermination of theory choice were addressed by Pablo
Acu&ntilde;a, particularly in the case of Lorentz&rsquo;s ether theory
and Einstein&rsquo;s special relativity (Acu&ntilde;a and Dieks 2014;
Acu&ntilde;a 2014a). Acu&ntilde;a (2014b) also analyses three
artificial cases of empirical equivalence, arguing that they are not
the result of practice of real science but cooked up by philosophers
of science.</p>

<h3 id="DynaScie">3.3 Dynamics of Science</h3>

<p>
Due to his close collaboration with Jean Piaget (Piaget and
Garc&iacute;a 1971, 1987), Rolando Garc&iacute;a became the author who
still represents genetic epistemology in Latin America (1997). In
particular, he developed with Piaget the idea of a parallelism between
psychogenesis and the evolution of sciences (Piaget and Garc&iacute;a
1983). More recently, Garc&iacute;a (2000) linked genetic epistemology
with the theory of complex systems.</p>

<p>
Already in the nineties, Oscar Nudler began to develop a view of the
dynamics of science in terms of conflicts (1990). This view became a
well-articulated model based on what he called &ldquo;controversy
space&rdquo; (Nudler 2002, 2004, in Spanish): a dynamic structure
composed of inter-related controversies, with a &ldquo;focus&rdquo;,
composed by the issues that are the main object of the disagreements,
and a &ldquo;common ground&rdquo;, which consists of the commitments
not subject to discussion within the controversy space. Controversy
spaces typically change by re-focalization which occurs when certain
assumptions move from the common ground to the focus. This model was
successfully applied to different scientific cases, such as the
origins of chaos theory, the debate about the relations between
chemistry and physics, the origins of molecular biology, and the
development of twentieth century American linguistics, among others
(see Nudler 2011).</p>

<p>
The philosophy of Thomas Kuhn attracted the interest of many Latin
American philosophers of science. For instance, during the 1980s, some
Cuban scholars focused on the Kuhnian concept of scientific revolution
(N&uacute;&ntilde;ez Jover 1985, 1989, in Spanish). In Uruguay, Mario
Otero (1997) edited a volume in Spanish about Kuhn with contributions
from his research group. After his retirement, the group was left in
the hands of Luc&iacute;a Lewowicz, who continued that line of
research (2004, 2005, in Spanish), focusing particularly on the
Kuhnian notion of taxonomic category (2007, in Spanish). In Colombia,
the research group of Jaramillo Uribe also compiled a collective
volume in Spanish devoted to the philosophy of Kuhn (Jaramillo Uribe
et al. 1997) and, in a more recent book also in Spanish, Guerrero Pino
(2003) considered the relevance of the Kuhnian philosophy for science
education. Recently, Pablo Lorenzano (2023a) revisited the Kuhnian
concept of paradigm, and Pablo Melogno and Leandro Giri (2023)
examined Kuhn&rsquo;s sources that had been understudied so far: the
Lowell Lectures of 1951 (<em>The Quest for Physical Theory</em>) and
the unpublished Notre Dame Lectures of 1980. Melogno (2022) also
offered a comparative analysis of Kuhn&rsquo;s historiographical
assumptions in <em>The Copernican Revolution</em> and <em>The
Structure of Scientific Revolutions</em>. In Argentina, N&eacute;lida
Gentile (2013) published a book in Spanish on incommensurability
commemorating the 50th anniversary of <em>The Structure</em>. The book
<em>Kuhn y el Cambio Cient&iacute;fico</em>, by Ana Rosa P&eacute;rez
Ransanz (1999), deserves particular attention, for it has been much
discussed in the Spanish-speaking world and, as a consequence, was
reprinted two times (2000, 2012). More recently, Melogno,
Hern&aacute;n Miguel, and Giri (2022) edited a volume that revisits
the impact and implications of Kuhn&rsquo;s philosophy from a
contemporary perspective. </p>

<p>
After getting his Ph.D. under the supervision of Paul Feyerabend,
Gonzalo Mun&eacute;var became one of the main international
specialists on the philosophy of the author (see the compilation of
his articles in Mun&eacute;var 2006, in Spanish). Moreover,
Mun&eacute;var (1998) advocates for an evolutionary philosophy that
leads to a thorough evolutionary relativism of scientific knowledge
which, nevertheless, is not an obstacle to a theory of relative truth.
From a different and original perspective, Carlos David Su&aacute;rez
Pascal (2021) proposes a biosemiotic and evolutionary conception of
theories, based on an analysis and comparison of philosopher Norwood
Russell Hanson&rsquo;s account of theories and zoologist Jakob von
Uexk&uuml;ll&rsquo;s theory of organisms (see also Su&aacute;rez
Pascal 2017).</p>

<h3 id="ScieReal">3.4 Scientific Realism</h3>

<p>
Christi&aacute;n Carman worked extensively on the problem of realism
in science. He offered a detailed elucidation of the term
&ldquo;scientific realism&rdquo; (2005a, in Spanish), and he
considered the theoretical-observational distinction in light of the
problem of realism (2005b, in Spanish). Carman also critically
analyzed Harr&eacute;&rsquo;s inductive argument for scientific
realism (2005c, in Spanish). Moreover, he reformulated the no-miracle
argument in order to apply it to simultaneous predictions (2010a, in
Spanish), in particular in the context of Ptolemy&rsquo;s planetary
theory (Carman and D&iacute;ez 2015). More recently, Carman appealed
to specific case studies to discuss scientific realism. For example,
together with Gonzalo Recio and the Spanish philosopher Jos&eacute;
D&iacute;ez, he considers Ptolemy&rsquo;s successful prediction of
Mars&rsquo; orbit from Kepler&rsquo;s perspective (D&iacute;ez, Recio,
and Carman 2022), and stresses the challenge that scientific realism
poses to the hypothesis of Intelligent Design (Carman 2022a).</p>

<p>
Some surveys of the arguments regarding the problem of realism were
also produced in Spanish. For instance, Bruno Borge (2015)
reconsidered the no-miracle argument 40 years after its formulation,
and Borge and N&eacute;lida Gentile (2019) compiled a volume on the
subject with contributions from Latin American authors.</p>

<p>
Recently, the work of Anjan Chakravartty has aroused the interest of
some authors. For instance, Gentile and Susana Lucero (2021) have
focused on the unifying and explanatory power of the selective realism
defended by Chakravartty, and Soto and Romero (2020) have argued for
local selective realism, which aims at providing a tool for defending
realism in the transition from classical to quantum electrodynamics.
In turn, Adriana Spehrs (2021) analyzes Chakravartty&rsquo;s
dispositionalist account of properties in order to assess whether
ontological pluralism can meet the challenge that conflicting models
pose to the scientific realism.</p>

<p>
In the last decade, several authors have dealt specifically with the
metaphysics of science. Cristi&aacute;n Soto has examined the current
state of the metaphysics of science debate (Soto 2015), as well as the
distinction between locally and globally applied naturalistic
metaphysics (Soto 2017). Diego Romero, Federico Benitez, and Soto
(2018) have developed a proposal for a coherent ontology of
fundamental entities drawing from the distinction between interaction
and framework theories. Another author who is particularly interested
in the metaphysics of science by focusing on disagreements is Bruno
Borge, who claims that some disagreements about scientific ontology
are better understood when epistemic goals and values are taken into
account (Borge 2021a), and considers the question of how scientific
peers should revise their beliefs (if at all) upon recognized
disagreement (Borge and Lo Guercio 2021). In turn, Jonas Becker
Arenhart and Raoni Wohnrath Arroyo address the problem of metaphysical
underdetermination to conclude that the available meta-metaphysical
criteria fail to deliver objectivity in theory choice (Arenhart and
Arroyo 2021) and claim that what is currently thought of as
scientifically respectful metaphysics may end up also being without
epistemic value (Arroyo and Arenhart 2022a).</p>

<h3 id="PlurScie">3.5 Pluralisms in Science</h3>

<p>
After the strong influence of logical empiricism and its claim for the
&ldquo;unity of science&rdquo;, in the last decades of the twentieth
century many pluralist approaches were proposed from different
perspectives. In Latin America, different pluralistic views have been
advanced.</p>

<p>
Although F&eacute;lix Schuster was a student of Mario Bunge and
Gregorio Klimovsky, he directed his interest to social sciences. In
this field, he defends methodological pluralism as the way to access
social reality (Schuster 1992, in Spanish).</p>

<p>
Roberto Torretti&rsquo;s view of scientific knowledge finds its roots
in his interpretation of Kant&rsquo;s philosophy (Torretti 1967).
According to Torretti, it does not follow from the transcendental
deduction of the categories that they are contained in a definitive
and immutable list; by admitting that the patterns ruling the
constitution of the objects of knowledge may change, &ldquo;Kant opens
a wide door to intellectual pluralism&rdquo; (2008: 87). From this
perspective, Torretti (2000) explicitly rejects the scientific realism
that conceives the aim of science as the development of a discourse
that &ldquo;cuts reality at its joints&rdquo; and agrees with Hilary
Putnam&rsquo;s pragmatic realism (Putnam 1987) on the basis of some
examples drawn from past and present scientific practice.</p>

<p>
Also under the influence of Putnam, but now of his internal realism
(Putnam 1981), Olimpia Lombardi and Ana Rosa P&eacute;rez Ransanz
(2012, in Spanish) propose an ontological pluralism that, instead of
being applied to the problem of theory change, finds its main
fertility in a synchronic sense: when theories embodying different
conceptual schemes are simultaneously accepted, it must be admitted
that different ontologies may coexist since each one of them is
constituted by its corresponding theory. This view, which denies the
ontological dependence of the supposedly &ldquo;secondary&rdquo;
disciplines or &ldquo;phenomenological&rdquo; theories regarding those
fields conceived as &ldquo;fundamental&rdquo;, has been applied to the
relationship between chemistry and physics with the purpose of
defending the ontological autonomy of the chemical world (Lombardi and
Labarca 2005); this view has sparked an intense debate in the field of
the philosophy of chemistry (it will be considered below, in the
subsection about the philosophy of chemistry). Lombardi has further
developed this Kantian-rooted ontological pluralism by stressing its
pragmatic content (2023a) and by distinguishing between diachronic and
synchronic ontological pluralisms (2023b).</p>

<h3 id="ReprScie">3.6 Representation in Science</h3>

<p>
The role played by models in science was studied in Latin America
since the first years of the twentieth century. In M&eacute;xico,
Alfredo L&oacute;pez Austin (2005) compiled a volume including five
contributions that explore the meaning and the nature of scientific
models. More recently, Mario Casanueva and Ximena
Gonz&aacute;lez-Grand&oacute;n (2016) edited a special issue of the
journal <em>Scientiae Studia</em>, whose articles fall into two
groups: those in the first group emphasize that models amplify our
capacities of representation, perception, and calculation; those in
the second stress the function of models in legitimating scientific
knowledge.</p>

<p>
Alejandro Cassini also paid close attention to the nature of
scientific models. In particular, he criticizes fictionalism, which
conceives models as useful fictions (Cassini 2013), and contends that
every scientific model has a target against those who claim that some
models do not (Cassini 2018). In turn, Hern&aacute;n Accorinti
discussed the problem of the autonomy of models with respect to
theories, with applications to chemistry, in particular, to the
different models of electronegativity (Accorinti 2019) and, in
collaboration with Juan Camilo Mart&iacute;nez Gonz&aacute;lez, to
molecular models in quantum chemistry, with special attention to the
role played by the Born-Oppenheimer approximation (Accorinti and
Mart&iacute;nez Gonz&aacute;lez 2022).</p>

<p>
In this field, Natalia Carrillo has developed a fruitful collaboration
with Tarja Knuuttila. They adopt an artifactual approach according to
which idealizations are holistic in nature, that is, they cannot be
locally undone without dismantling the model (Carrillo and Knuuttila
2021, 2022). And they argue that mechanical philosophy in life
sciences, which involves the decomposition of a system into its parts,
does not suit models whose epistemic strategy is not decompositional
(Carrillo and Knuuttila 2023).</p>

<p>
Although not directly concerned with models, an interesting volume in
Spanish about the epistemic role of images in science was published as
the result of a workshop held in Mexico City in 2007 (Casanueva and
Bola&ntilde;os 2009). In the introduction to the volume, the editors
refer to the &ldquo;<em>pictorial turn</em>&rdquo; to stress the
increasing relevance of pictorial representation as an epistemic
vehicle for science, where &ldquo;pictorial&rdquo; includes not only
visual pictures but also tactile and auditory representations. In this
context it is worth mentioning the role of metaphors in science:
Sergio Mart&iacute;nez and Carrillo discuss examples from the history
of science that illustrate different ways in which metaphors play a
role in scientific innovation (Mart&iacute;nez and Carrillo 2022) and
stress the relation between metaphors and abstraction (Carrillo and
Mart&iacute;nez 2023).</p>

<p>
In the domain of physics, Pablo Acu&ntilde;a (2023) presents the
development of astronomical models from Eudoxus to Kepler as a
case-study that vindicates Henk de Regt&rsquo;s account of scientific
understanding. In the field of biology, Chabel El-Hani, in
collaboration with several authors working outside Latin America
(Poliseli et al. 2022), addresses the contributions of the recent
mechanistic philosophy of science to the scientific practice of model
building in ecology.</p>

<h3 id="CausLawsNatu">3.7 Causation and Laws of Nature</h3>

<p>
Although Mario Bunge&rsquo;s already classical book <em>Causality</em>
(1959a) was a landmark in the study of causation, it was only several
decades later that the interest on causation took off in the region.
Eduardo Flichman developed a &ldquo;deflationist&rdquo; view of
causation according to which causation is not an ontological relation
between events but an anthropomorphic asymmetric relation that
speakers project over reality. From this perspective, Flichman (1989)
criticized the counterfactual theory of causation proposed by David
Lewis (1973) by showing that clear cases of causation can be
meaningfully reversed and, therefore, challenge the supposed asymmetry
of causation.</p>

<p>
This criticism sparked an interesting debate in the Mexican journal
<em>Critica</em> during the 1990s. Dorothy Edgington (1990) accepted
Flichman&rsquo;s criticism as an argument against the possibility of
analyzing the concept of causation. Horacio Abeledo (1995), in turn,
showed that there would be a &ldquo;formal&rdquo; way out of
Flichman&rsquo;s criticism, but with no philosophical support. From an
opposite perspective, Helen Beebee (1997) explicitly responded to
Flichman&rsquo;s argument and to Abeledo&rsquo;s conclusion by arguing
that the putative counter-example presented by Flichman is not in fact
a counter-example after all. Both Flichman and Abeledo reacted to
Beebee&rsquo;s paper. On the basis of a refutation of Beebee&rsquo;s
argument, Flichman (2000) elaborated on his criticism of Lewis&rsquo;s
theory and his defense of an acausal position. Finally, Abeledo (2000)
offered a clear and detailed summary of the whole controversy, adding
new arguments against Beebee&rsquo;s view but stressing his
disagreements with Flichman&rsquo;s position.</p>

<p>
Other Latin American authors were interested in causation. For
example, Sergio Mart&iacute;nez (1997, in Spanish) provides a detailed
review of the role of causation in scientific explanation along the
history of science. In Santiago de Chile, Wilfredo Quezada Pulido
leads a research group mainly devoted to study physical causation. In
his published works in Spanish, Quesada Pulido compares the theories
of causal transference, of causal processes, and of conserved
quantities (2002), and analyzes the manipulability theory of causation
in the light of the problem of anthropomorphism (2007). More recently,
Fernanda Samaniego uses the manipulability approach to define a notion
of &ldquo;explanatory depth&rdquo; (2014) and to account for spin-echo
experiments (2013, 2015). More recently, by appealing to the example
of ideal gases, Samaniego (2022) discusses James Woodward&rsquo;s
article &ldquo;Flagpoles anyone? Causal and explanatory
asymmetries&rdquo;.</p>

<p>
His work on causation led Flichman (1990, 1995) to discuss the concept
of scientific law: according to him, the distinction between laws of
nature and accidental uniformities depends on the role they play in a
scientific theory; moreover &ldquo;hard&rdquo; and &ldquo;soft&rdquo;
accidental uniformities must be carefully distinguished because the
latter are frequently confused with laws of nature. Pablo Lorenzano
(1998, 2007, in Spanish) also reflects upon the concept of law of
nature in relation to the existence of biological laws.</p>

<p>
In 2019, Bruno Borge and Renato Cani edited a special issue of the
Brazilian journal <em>Principia</em> devoted to laws of nature, which
included contributions of Cristi&aacute;n Soto, who, in collaboration
with Otavio Bueno (Soto and Bueno 2019), proposes an inferential
conception of physical laws, which draws from the epistemic
indispensability argument in philosophy of mathematics (Soto 2019);
and of N&eacute;lida Gentile (2019), who presents some drawbacks faced
by the regularity view of Mill-Ramsey-Lewis, by Armstrong&rsquo;s
necessitarian view and by Mumford&rsquo;s realist lawlessness.</p>

<p>
In recent years, Aldo Filomeno has analyzed the much-discussed
Humeanism about natural laws. The author shares the Humean spirit when
claiming that the apparently non-accidental regularities are the
result of a statistical necessity rather than of a primitive physical
necessity (Filomeno 2019). By highlighting the unjustified implicit
assignment of equiprobability to each possible Humean mosaic, Filomeno
(2021) concludes that the &ldquo;cosmic coincidence&rdquo; objection
to Humeanism should not be dismissed. Filomeno (2023) also argues that
Humean supervenience does not need to endorse a standard version of
truthmaker maximalism and, therefore, Humean supervenience and the
Growing-Block Universe are compatible.</p>

<h3 id="PhilHistScie">3.8 Philosophical History of Science</h3>

<p>
The history of science from a philosophical perspective has been
extensively studied in Latin America. For instance, in Argentina
Guillermo Boido has strongly promoted the area; his book in Spanish on
Galileo (Boido 1996) not only offers a historical narrative, but also
explains historiographic discussions in light of the historical
record. In Colombia, Mauricio Nieto Olarte (2000, 2007) developed
relevant research work in Spanish on the origins of science in the
region during the colonial period. In Mexico, Laura Ben&iacute;tez
published several works in Spanish on early science (e.g.,
Ben&iacute;tez 1993, 2000, 2004), and developed a long and fruitful
collaboration with Jos&eacute; Antonio Robles about science in
modernity (e.g., Ben&iacute;tez and Robles 2000, 2006; Robles and
Ben&iacute;tez 2004). More recently, Ben&iacute;tez (2019) focused on
the methodological framework within which Sor Juana In&eacute;s de la
Cruz examines sensibility and understanding. Also in M&eacute;xico,
Godfrey Guillaumin studied the historical evolution of the notion of
scientific evidence (2005, in Spanish) and the deep cognitive changes
generated by measurements in the Scientific Revolution (2017).</p>

<p>
Some philosophers of science of the region also manifested their
interest in particular events of the history of science. For instance,
Pablo Mariconda analyzed Galileo&rsquo;s tide theory (1999, in
Portuguese), the simple machines designed by Galileo (2008, in
Portuguese), and Galileo&rsquo;s argument for the autonomy of science
(Lacey and Mariconda 2012); he also studied the method of astronomy
according to Kepler (Tossato and Mariconda 2010, in Portuguese). In
turn, Carlos Alberto Cardona Su&aacute;rez examined the methodology
used by Kepler to discover a quantitative law of refraction (Cardona
Su&aacute;rez 2016; Cardona Su&aacute;rez and Guti&eacute;rrez
Valderrama 2020). By contrast, Sergio Orozco-Echeverri focused his
work on the impact and repercussions of Renaissance science and
modernity in the Iberian-American world (Orozco-Echeverri and
Molina-Betancur 2019, 2021; Orozco-Echeverri 2023).</p>

<p>
In turn, Alejandro Cassini and Marcelo Levinas developed a fruitful
collaboration mainly published in Spanish, studying different aspects
of the history of physics at the beginning of twentieth century,
particularly regarding Einstein&rsquo;s works: Einstein&rsquo;s
reinterpretation of Michelson-Morley experiment (Cassini and Levinas
2005), his explanations of photoelectric effect (Cassini and Levinas
2008; Cassini, Levinas, and Pringe 2015) and of the Compton effect
(Cassini, Levinas, and Pringe 2013), his reinterpretation of Fizeau
experiment (Cassini and Levinas 2019), as well as the role played by
the ether in the conceptual change to special relativity (Cassini and
Levinas 2009). In the quantum context, Olival Freire Jr. (2015)
published a book that traces the passionate foundational controversies
that accompanied the ripening of quantum physics during the second
half of the twentieth century.</p>

<p>
El&iacute;as Fuentes Guill&eacute;n focused his interest on Bolzano.
He reports Bolzano&rsquo;s postulation to the chair of Elementary
Mathematics at Prague University (Fuentes Guill&eacute;n and Crippa
2021) and studies Bolzano&rsquo;s contributions to logic (Fuentes
Guill&eacute;n 2023) and to mathematics (Fuentes Guill&eacute;n and
Mart&iacute;nez Adame 2020; Bair et al. 2020, 2022).</p>

<p>
The history of biological sciences has been the interest of Ana
Barahona, who focused mainly on the case of Mexico: with different
colleagues, she considers how European ideas about human species and
race in the scientific mainstream were deployed in the very
distinctive situations of Mexico (Torrens and Barahona 2019), she
analyzes the teaching of biological evolution in Mexican socialist
textbooks in the 1930s (Torrens, Rodr&iacute;guez Caso, and Barahona
2021), and she recalls the first time that cytogenetic techniques had
been used in the Olympics in Mexico in 1968 (Barahona 2022). From a
more general viewpoint, she offers a critical and comparative review
of the historiographical studies on biogeography
(Bueno-Hern&aacute;ndez, Barahona, et al. 2023). For a more detailed
report of the history of biology in the region, see the entry
&ldquo;Philosophy of Biology in Latin America&rdquo; (Lorenzano
2023).</p>

<p>
The works of Christi&aacute;n Carman deserve a special mention, since
their quantity and quality turn him to be considered a first level
international specialist in ancient astronomy. Precisely because of
the volume of his production, here we will only refer to a selection.
Carman&rsquo;s first works focused on Ptolemy&rsquo;s calculations and
explanations (Carman 2009, 2010a, 2015; Recio and Carman 2018), making
him an international expert on Ptolemy. His interest was also directed
to other authors, such as Aristarchus (2014), Martianus Capella
(2016), Copernicus (2017a), and Heraclides of Pontus (2017b). In a
further line of research, Carman&rsquo;s collaboration with the
renowned scholar James Evans for the detailed study of the Antikythera
mechanism resulted in several very relevant works (Evans, Carman, and
Thorndike 2010; Carman, Thorndike, and Evans 2012; Carman and Evans
2014; Evans and Carman 2019). More recently, Carman turned his
attention to technical aspects of Tycho Brahe&rsquo;s work (2020,
2021, 2022b; Carman and Recio 2022) and to the accuracy of
Kepler&rsquo;s results (Carman 2022c; Pelegrin and Carman 2019).</p>

<h3 id="ScieSociValu">3.9 Science, Society, and Values</h3>

<p>
In Latin America, the discussions about science and values have
traditionally focused on the question of the dependence of scientific
research in Latin American countries on the agenda set by central
countries. Due to their local interest, most of the material was
written in Spanish. In 1971, a debate, remembered until today for its
philosophical and political significance, confronted Oscar Varsavsky
and Gregorio Klimovsky in Argentina. For Varsavsky (1971), since
science is essentially ideology-laden, ideology must appear explicitly
in scientific policy as a guide toward a new social order. Klimovsky
(1971), by contrast, advocated for a neutral basic science: politics
appear mostly in the application of scientific knowledge. The original
debate was complemented with the contribution of other prominent
Argentine thinkers and appeared in 1975 as the book <em>Ciencia y
Ideolog&iacute;a. Aportes pol&eacute;micos</em> (Klimovsky et al.
1975). In the same year, Jorge Sabato (1975) compiled a significant
book with articles by more than twenty specialists about ideology in
science, relations between science, technology, and society, the
structural scientific-technological dependence of Latin America, the
production of technology, and the planning of scientific-technological
development in Latin American countries. The lively debates of those
years were drastically interrupted by the military coup
d&rsquo;&egrave;tat in Argentina in 1976.</p>

<p>
The claim for a Latin American science, guided by regional interests
and ideological views, is in resonance with those philosophical and
sociological studies, like that of Enrique Dussel (1995) which
denounces the Eurocentric &ldquo;myth of modernity&rdquo; that
justifies the superiority of European culture over Native American
cultures. In turn, the need to contextualize scientific knowledge in
the framework of social needs of a particular community also appears
in the works of Rolando Garc&iacute;a (1981) under the concept of
interdisciplinary research, that is, a research that combines
different theoretical approaches in the search for solving localized
social requirements. More recently, Ambrosio Velasco G&oacute;mez
(2004) has considered that moral and political questions are at the
core of the epistemological and methodological problems of scientific
theories, and that the widespread idea that political and even ethical
decisions should be based on scientific knowledge has strong
authoritarian implications. In turn, M&oacute;nica
G&oacute;mez-Salazar (2017) claims that cultural neutrality, based on
the idea of equality without any distinction of color, sex, language,
religion, or political opinion, really favors white racism and
cultural imperialism of the liberal way of life.</p>

<p>
The interest in how social knowledge is produced in Latin America has
grown during the last decades. An example of this interest is the book
of Leandro Rodr&iacute;guez Medina (2014) which examines the
circulation of knowledge within globalization, focusing on the
differences between centers and peripheries of knowledge production in
the social sciences, and in the ways in which foreign ideas shape
peripheral fields.</p>

<p>
Two philosophers of science, who are well-known in the Latin American
communities, were also very interested in issues connected with social
and political values in science, although from different perspectives.
Since the 1990s, Le&oacute;n Oliv&eacute; (1988 [1993], in Spanish)
stood at the interface between the philosophy and the sociology of
knowledge, trying to explain the double nature of knowledge as a
social construct and a representation of reality. More recently, his
interest focused on how technology has pervaded contemporary society,
modeling both knowledge and values (Oliv&eacute; 2007, in Spanish).
Ricardo G&oacute;mez, by contrast, develops his position in open
confrontation with neoliberalism (2002, 2017a, in Spanish). On this
basis, he considers that the ethical dimension of science and
technology should stand against neoliberal principles from a clear
political position (G&oacute;mez 2017b, in Spanish).</p>

<p>
The interaction between scientific activities and values has been the
interest of Pablo Mariconda (Lacey and Mariconda 2014a, 2014b, in
Portuguese). In particular, Mariconda (2014) discusses the
technological risks associated with transgenic agriculture. Along the
same lines, Guillermo Folgera produced two works in Spanish in which
he analyzes the techno-scientific discourse regarding genetically
modified organisms (Folguera, Carrizo, and Massarini 2014) and
denounces the omission of risks in the use of such organisms (Francese
and Folguera 2018).</p>

<p>
In the context of science, society, and values, studies that combine
the reflection upon scientific knowledge with gender matters must be
mentioned. For instance, Fabrizzio (now Siobhan) Guerrero Mc Manus
(2016) provides Spanish-speaking readers with an overview of a
feminism that seeks to develop a critical framework aimed at
detecting, exposing, and correcting the many gender biases nowadays
present in the sciences (see also Mc Manus 2019). In this context, the
works of Diana Maff&iacute;a in Spanish cannot be forgotten since she
has critically analyzed the links between gender and science in the
past twenty years or so (e.g., Maff&iacute;a 2001, 2005, 2006, 2007;
Rietti and Maff&iacute;a 2005). More recently, Manuela
Fern&aacute;ndez-Pinto has explored how dissent on gender bias in
academia affects science and society (Leuscher and
Fern&aacute;ndez-Pinto 2021) and has highlighted the long and rich
history of the Latin American women&rsquo;s participation in the
production of knowledge (Harding, P&eacute;rez-Bustos, and
Fern&aacute;ndez-Pinto, 2019).</p>

<p>
Mariana C&oacute;rdoba approaches the problem of personal identity
from a philosophical and political perspective. She focuses on the
Argentinian Gender Identity Law in order to argue that gender identity
is biotechnologically and legally produced (C&oacute;rdoba 2020). But
her main interest has been personal identity in the context of
children&rsquo;s appropriation in Argentinian dictatorship
(C&oacute;rdoba 2021; C&oacute;rdoba, Ferreira Ruiz, and Alassia
2021).</p>

<p>
During the last decade, Fern&aacute;ndez-Pinto has developed an
extensive work on the links between science and society. In
particular, she has focused his interest on the social and epistemic
consequences of the current commercialization of scientific research
(2015a, 2015b, 2017, 2018, 2020a, 2020b). She also points out how
certain dissents are epistemically and socially detrimental as they
contribute to racism in society and to a social atmosphere that is
hostile to science (Leuscher and Fern&aacute;ndez-Pinto 2022), and
explores ways of counteracting cognitive biases that lead scientists
to wrong conclusions (Fern&aacute;ndez-Pinto 2023).</p>

<h2 id="PhilPartScie">4. Philosophy of Particular Sciences</h2>

<h3 id="PhilPhys">4.1 Philosophy of Physics</h3>

<p>
Although Mario Bunge and Roberto Torretti were central figures for the
philosophy of physics in Latin America, their early emigration
prevented them from starting research lines around their works. As a
consequence, the development of the philosophy of physics in the
region is relatively recent.</p>

<p>
Quantum mechanics is one of the focuses of the research group led by
Olimpia Lombardi which developed its work in two directions: the
interpretation of the theory and the analysis of the meaning of
decoherence. Regarding the first topic, Lombardi and Mario Castagnino
proposed the Modal-Hamiltonian Interpretation of quantum mechanics: a
realist, non-collapse interpretation that endows the Hamiltonian with
a determining role. The interpretation proved to be effective in
explaining ideal and non-ideal measurements and many other well-known
physical situations such as hydrogen atom, Zeeman effect, fine
structure, etc. (Lombardi and Castagnino 2008). The interpretation was
reformulated in a Galilean invariant form (Ardenghi, Castagnino, and
Lombardi 2009; Lombardi, Castagnino, and Ardenghi 2010), and was
applied to further situations, such as the non-collapse account of
consecutive measurements in physics (Ardenghi, Lombardi, and Narvaja
2013), the understanding of quantum decoherence (Lombardi, Ardenghi,
Fortin, and Castagnino 2011), the view of quantum measurement in
informational terms (Lombardi, Fortin, and L&oacute;pez 2015), and the
problem of optical isomerism in chemistry (Fortin, Lombardi, and
Mart&iacute;nez Gonz&aacute;lez 2016, 2018). More recently, the
interpretation served as a basis to define the time of quantum events
from a relational perspective (Fortin, Lombardi, and Pasqualini 2022).
In addition, the modal-Hamiltonian interpretation proposes a
bundle-of-properties ontology that adequately accounts for
contextuality and indistinguishability (da Costa, Lombardi, and
Lastiri 2013; da Costa and Lombardi 2014; Lombardi 2023c), but without
preventing the emergence of particles under certain particular
circumstances (Lombardi and Dieks 2016). This ontology of properties
has been formalized by means of Krause&rsquo;s quasi-set theory
(Holik, Jorge, Krause, and Lombardi 2022), and has been applied to
solve the problem of entanglement in the case of indistinguishability
(Fortin and Lombardi 2022;Lombardi 2023d).</p>

<p>
By stressing the distinction between collapse and decoherence, Osvaldo
Pessoa (1997) criticized the assumption that decoherence solves the
measurement problem. Following Pessoa&rsquo;s view, Castagnino,
Sebastian Fortin, and Lombardi (2010) deepened the criticisms of the
orthodox approach to decoherence (see also Lombardi, Fortin, and
Castagnino 2012; Fortin and Lombardi 2014, 2017), proposed a new
approach for closed systems (Castagnino and Lombardi 2004; Fortin and
Lombardi 2018), and developed a general conceptual framework for
decoherence in closed and open systems (Castagnino, Laura, and
Lombardi 2007). Based on this new perspective, the research group
offered a particular view of the classical limit of quantum mechanics
(Castagnino and Lombardi 2005; Fortin and Lombardi 2016), applied it
to the problem of defining the quantum ergodic hierarchy (Castagnino
and Lombardi 2007), and stressed the role of the correspondence
principle in the understanding of decoherence (Fortin and Lombardi
2019).</p>

<p>
In the subtle frontier between logic and physics, D&eacute;cio Krause
developed an impressive work related to the quantum challenges to the
notions of identity and individuality. Already in his Ph.D.
dissertation, under the supervision of Newton da Costa, Krause
supplied a semantics to the so-called &ldquo;Schr&ouml;dinger
logic&rdquo; (da Costa and Krause 1994, 1997) designed to account for
elementary quantum particles. This work led him to formulate his
<em>quasi-set theory</em> (Krause 1991, 1992, 1996a, 1996b), according
to which there are urelements for which identity makes no sense.
Krause&rsquo;s semi-extensional quasi-set theory was compared with the
intensional quaset theory developed by Maria Luisa dalla Chiara and
Giuliano Toraldo di Francia (dalla Chiara, Giuntini, and Krause 1998),
and was applied to particular problems in the foundations of quantum
mechanics (Sant&rsquo;Anna and Krause 1997; Krause, Sant&rsquo;Anna,
and Volkov 1999; Krause 2000; Domenech, Holik, and Krause 2008).</p>

<p>
Krause also developed an intense collaboration with Steven French to
develop a concept of individuality for the quantum ontology (Krause
and French 1995, 2007; French and Krause 1995, 1999, 2003); they also
advanced some ideas about individuality in quantum field theory
(French and Krause 2010). This collaboration gave rise to a very
relevant book on the matter (French and Krause 2006), which discusses
the problem of individuality in philosophy and in classical and
quantum physics and articulates quasi-set theory as a theory for
non-individuals.</p>

<p>
More recently, Krause produced a relevant collaborative work with
Jonas Arenhart, his former Ph.D. student, about quantum
non-individuality (Krause and Arenhart 2012, 2016a; see also Arenhart
2017) and its compatibility with Einstein&rsquo;s realism (Krause and
Arenhart 2014). They also examined the view of quantum particles as
individuals in a primitive sense (Arenhart and Krause 2014a, 2014b).
This collaboration led to a recent book about the logical foundations
of scientific theories (Krause and Arenhart 2016b). In his more recent
works, Krause continues analyzing the logic of indiscernibility: he
advocates for a metaphysics of non-individuals, conceived as entities
to which the standard theory of identity of classical logic and set
theory does not apply (Krause, Arenhart, and Bueno 2022, Krause 2023),
connects indistinguishability with contextuality (de Barros, Holik,
and Krause, 2022), and offers an interpretation of the quantifiers
that avoids the &ldquo;collapse of quantifiers&rdquo; when they
quantify over indiscernible objects (Krause 2022).</p>

<p>
Still in the field of the interpretation of quantum mechanics,
El&iacute;as Okon and Daniel Sudarsky (2014a, 2014b) criticized Robert
Griffiths&rsquo;s consistent histories approach by arguing that it is
interpretively vague and does not solve the measurement problem. These
works were rebutted by Griffiths (2015), and the rebuttal was
immediately answered by Okon and Sudarsky (2015a) by claiming that the
consistent histories interpretation introduces anthropomorphic terms
not contained in the formalism. In turn, based on Okon and
Sudarsky&rsquo;s criticism, Marcelo Losada and Lombardi (2018) defend
a &ldquo;formalism of contextual histories&rdquo; which is free from
the shortcomings of Griffiths&rsquo;s proposal.</p>

<p>
Given the need for an observer-independent interpretation of quantum
mechanics for cosmology, Okon and Sudarsky (2014c) defended an
objective collapse theory for the application to cosmology and quantum
gravity and, on this basis, they proposed an adaptation of objective
collapse models to a general relativistic context (2018a). The authors
also examined the black hole information loss paradox as a situation
that can be accounted for by collapse interpretations (Okon and
Sudarsky 2015b, 2017, 2018b) and the status of the conservation
principles in different contexts, in particular, in semiclassical
gravity (Maudlin, Okon, and Sudarsky 2020).</p>

<p>
Other interpretations of quantum mechanics have also drawn the
interest of Latin American authors. For instance, Ricardo
Muci&ntilde;o, Okon, and Sudarsky (2022) offer a strong criticism of
Rovelli&rsquo;s Relational Quantum Mechanics, and Lombardi and Juan
Sebasti&aacute;n Ardenghi (2022) compare Relational Quantum Mechanics
and the Modal-Hamiltonian Interpretation. Arroyo and Arenhart (2022)
analyze the debate concerning the existence of worlds in Everettian
Quantum Mechanics. In turn, Jorge Manero focuses on Bohmian Mechanics:
in this context he proposes a relational notion of distinguishable
object that should be conceived from a structuralist point of view
(Manero 2021). Beyond the limits of Bohmian Mechanics, Manero (2019)
provides a formal and accurate description of the structural-based
ontology posited by classical mechanics, quantum mechanics, and
special relativity.</p>

<p>
The Frauchiger-Renner argument, which sparked a heated debate since
its first presentation in 2016, was also analyzed by Latin American
philosophers of physics. According to Fortin and Lombardi (2020), the
argument leads to a dilemma: either it is an original way to reproduce
the proof of quantum contextuality, or it is illegitimate because it
appeals to inferences forbidden by the algebraic structure of quantum
propositions. From a similar perspective, Muci&ntilde;o and Okon
(2020) argue that all the lessons learned from the Frauchiger-Renner
result are essentially contained within the original EPR paper.</p>

<p>
Other aspects and interpretations of quantum mechanics have also been
explored. For instance, Sergio Mart&iacute;nez discussed the physical
content of the Luders Rule (1990, 1991), Pessoa (2005) proposed a
modal logical treatment of quantum mechanics, and Pablo Acu&ntilde;a
(2016b) pointed out the difficulties in defining the notion of
inertial trajectory in Bohmian mechanics (Acu&ntilde;a 2019). In turn,
Rodolfo Gambini, Luis Pedro Garc&iacute;a-Pintos, and Jorge Pullin
(2010, 2011) devised an interpretation that offers a solution to the
quantum measurement problem based on the loss of coherence due to the
use of realistic clocks. Cristian L&oacute;pez, in collaboration with
the Italian researcher Andrea Oldofredi, points out the limitations of
the much discussed distinction between Psi-ontic and Psi-epistemic
quantum models (Oldofredi and L&oacute;pez 2020). Regarding
non-locality, Gerardo Sanju&aacute;n Ciepielewski, Okon, and Sudarsky
(2023) introduce a fully local and superdeterministic model that, by
explicitly violating &ldquo;settings independence&rdquo;, reproduces
the predictions of quantum mechanics. In turn, Pablo Acu&ntilde;a
revisits von Neumann&rsquo;s Theorem and the recent debate about its
relevance (Acu&ntilde;a 2021a) and argues that the import of the
Kochen-Specker theorem gets substantially weakened when von
Neumann&rsquo;s and Gleason&rsquo;s theorems are taken into account
(Acu&ntilde;a 2021b). From a more general perspective, Acu&ntilde;a
(2021c) discusses what interpreting quantum mechanics means and
concludes that it supplies a case of predictively equivalent rival
theories.</p>

<p>
The foundations of relativistic mechanics have also begun to awaken
the interest of Latin American scholars. For instance, Acu&ntilde;a
(2016) critically assesses the debate concerning the direction of the
explanation between Minkowski spacetime and the Lorentz invariance of
dynamical laws. Diego Maltrana also focuses on relativity from
different perspectives: in collaboration with Federico Ben&iacute;tez
and Pablo Razeto-Barry, he offers a new interpretation of the equation
&ldquo;<em>E</em>=<em>mc</em><sup>2</sup>&rdquo; by proposing that
mass, as a property, can be considered to emerge from energy
(Ben&iacute;tez, Maltrana, and Razeto-Barry 2022); in collaboration
with Manuel Herrera and Ben&iacute;tez, he generalizes the difference
between &ldquo;framework&rdquo; and &ldquo;interaction&rdquo;
theories, which in turn is based on Einstein&rsquo;s distinction
between &ldquo;principle&rdquo; and &ldquo;constructive&rdquo;
theories (Maltrana, Herrera, and Ben&iacute;tez 2022); and in
collaboration with Nicol&aacute;s Sep&uacute;lveda-Quiroz, he applies
that difference to general relativity (Maltrana,
Sep&uacute;lveda-Quiroz 2022).</p>

<p>
The problem of time&rsquo;s arrow was addressed by Castagnino,
Lombardi and collaborators by elaborating on John Earman&rsquo;s
heresy (1974) according to which the arrow of time is a geometrical
property of the universe (Castagnino, Lombardi, and Lara 2003). This
global arrow is transferred to the local domain as an energy flow that
points to the same time direction on the entire spacetime (Castagnino
and Lombardi 2009), which in turn supplies the foundations for local
irreversible theories (Aiello, Castagnino, and Lombardi 2008).
Castagnino and Lombardi also collaborated with Manuel Gadella, one of
the authors of the time-asymmetric quantum mechanics, in order to
analyze irreversibility and time&rsquo;s arrow in the quantum realm
(Castagnino, Gadella, and Lombardi 2006), a work recently followed by
Cristian L&oacute;pez (2019). More recently, Cristian L&oacute;pez
faces the problem of time reversal from a metaphysical perspective: he
claims that any account of time reversal presupposes modal,
metaphysical, and heuristic facets (L&oacute;pez 2021a), argues that
the concept of time reversal may be understood differently depending
on one&rsquo;s metaphysics about time, laws, and a theory&rsquo;s
basic properties (L&oacute;pez 2023a), and proposes a Humean
interpretation of time-reversal symmetry according to which it is an
epistemic virtue of the best system, not a property of the Humean
mosaic (L&oacute;pez and Esfeld 2023). L&oacute;pez has also analyzed
the concept of time reversal in the quantum case (L&oacute;pez 2021b)
and considered the problem of the arrow of time in orthodox quantum
mechanics and in spontaneous collapse theories (L&oacute;pez 2022a,
2022b).</p>

<p>
Following the growing interest in symmetries in physics, some Latin
American authors have dealt with the subject. In the same line as his
works on time reversal, L&oacute;pez (2023b) explores the
relationships between symmetries and metaphysics. Based on the
analysis of Noether&rsquo;s theorems, Maltrana (2015) argues for the
priority of conserved quantities over symmetries. In turn, Aldo
Filomeno (2016) claims that any metaphysical account of fundamental
laws that expects symmetry restoration up to the fundamental level is
not fully satisfactory.</p>

<h3 id="PhilChem">4.2 Philosophy of Chemistry</h3>

<p>
Although the philosophy of chemistry is a relatively young
subdiscipline in philosophy of science, it has attracted the interest
of several researchers in Latin America.</p>

<p>
The group led by Olimpia Lombardi worked on the topic since 2005, when
a paper advocating for the ontological autonomy of chemistry (Lombardi
and Labarca 2005) was published. The paper sparked a hot debate which
began with a criticism by Paul Needham (2006) that was immediately
responded by Lombardi and Labarca (2006), and was followed by many
other authors. In the meantime, Labarca and Lombardi (2010) also
argued for the existence of orbitals in the ontology of chemistry,
relying on ontological pluralism. On the basis of the impact of her
view, Lombardi reviewed and organized the different criticisms and
offered a systematic response to them (2014a); in turn, with Mariana
C&oacute;rdoba, she stressed the Kantian roots of her ontological
pluralism (C&oacute;rdoba and Lombardi 2013).</p>

<p>
Given her antireductionist perspective, Lombardi (2013, 2014b) also
criticized the book of Hinne Hettema (2012), <em>Reducing Chemistry to
Physics</em>, stressing the many difficulties that must be faced by
those who insist on the reduction of chemistry to physics; the papers
received an immediate reply from Hettema (2014).</p>

<p>
The problems regarding the relations between chemistry and physics
were addressed by Lombardi&rsquo;s group from various perspectives. In
particular, they brought to light several interpretive issues of
quantum mechanics that lead to conceptual tensions when the theory is
used in chemistry (Lombardi and Castagnino 2010), pointed out the
difficulties in reducing molecular structure to quantum mechanics
(Mart&iacute;nez Gonz&aacute;lez, Fortin, and Lombardi 2019; Fortin
and Lombardi 2021), and argued that quantum decoherence does not solve
the problem of isomerism (Fortin, Lombardi, and Mart&iacute;nez
Gonz&aacute;lez 2016). Moreover, Juan Camilo Mart&iacute;nez
Gonz&aacute;lez (2020) considers the possibility of an ontology
specific to quantum chemistry and different from that of quantum
mechanics. The members of the group have also begun to face the issue
of the relationship between chemistry and quantum mechanics from other
theoretical perspectives, such as Bohmian mechanics (Fortin, Lombardi,
and Mart&iacute;nez Gonz&aacute;lez 2017; this last paper was
critically assessed by Giovanni Villani, Elena Ghibaudi, and Luigi
Cerruti 2018) and the Quantum Theory of Atoms in Molecules (QTAIM)
(Jaimes Arriaga, Fortin, and Lombardi 2019). In collaboration with
Ch&eacute;rif Matta, one of the world&rsquo;s leading specialists in
QTAIM, they conceived the theory as a non-reductive bridge between
quantum mechanics and molecular chemistry (Matta, Lombardi, and
Arriaga 2020; Lombardi and Matta 2022).</p>

<p>
As a continuation of her previous work in Spanish, Lombardi (2012)
offered a critical analysis of Ilya Prigogine&rsquo;s proposals. In
turn, with Luc&iacute;a Lewowicz, she analyzed the ontological
category of stuff as required by macro-chemistry (Lewowicz and
Lombardi 2013). The problem of the categories underlying the chemical
discourse was also addressed in the context of Lombardi&rsquo;s group
by Mariana C&oacute;rdoba and Alfio Zambon (2017) for the particular
case of nano-materials. These authors also considered the inter-theory
links involved in the relationships between nanochemistry, molecular
chemistry, and quantum mechanics (C&oacute;rdoba and Zambon 2021).</p>

<p>
A particular mention is deserved by Zambon&rsquo;s (2018) completely
new representation of the periodic system based on atomic-number
triads, and its implications for science teaching and communication
(Zambon 2019). Zambon (2022) also proposes to replace the traditional
categories of cause and effect by that of interaction or reciprocal
action for the understanding of chemical reaction phenomena.</p>

<p>
Guillermo Restrepo focused his interest on how formal tools can be
applied to chemistry. With Jos&eacute; Luis Villaveces, he noted the
resemblance between Leibniz&rsquo;s and Lavoisier&rsquo;s programs
regarding a <em>lingua philosophica</em> for understanding nature
(Restrepo and Villaveces 2011) and reviewed the origins of
mathematical thinking in chemistry (Restrepo and Villaveces 2012).
Restrepo also analyzed the mathematical aspects of the periodic law
(Restrepo and Pach&oacute;n 2007) and considered the different
foundational aspects of the field called &ldquo;mathematical
chemistry&rdquo; (2013; Restrepo and Villaveces 2013). Restrepo has
been working in Germany since 2014 where he still produces interesting
contributions to the philosophy of chemistry.</p>

<p>
In the blurred boundaries between chemistry and biology, biochemistry
has been arousing some interest in Latin America during the last
decades. For instance, Pio Garc&iacute;a analyzes serendipity
discoveries in biochemistry, that is, those accidental findings made
when the discoverer is in quest for something else (Garc&iacute;a
2008), and argues that simulations were implicit in biochemistry in
the classical dichotomy in vivo-in vitro long before computers arrived
(Garc&iacute;a 2015). In turn, Gabriel Vallejo, together with two
non-Latin American colleagues, rejects the reductionist bias in the
conceptualization of the relationship between the composition,
structure and function of macromolecules like proteins, and argues
that it requires the analysis of the dynamical interplay between the
micro-level of parts and the macro-level of relational structures
(Santos, Vallejos, and Vecchi 2020). Karina Alleva and Luc&iacute;a
Federico, together with the Spanish scholar Jos&eacute; D&iacute;ez,
argue that a model-theoretic notion of theory can be successfully
applied to the case of allosterism (Alleva, D&iacute;ez, and Federico
2017). More recently, Fiorela Alassia (2023) adopted a
process-ontology perspective to understand the case of ligand
receptors and receptor-mediated biosignaling.</p>

<p>
The development of the technological aspects of chemistry has been the
interest of Jos&eacute; Antonio Chamizo (2013, 2017, 2019) with
applications to chemistry education.</p>

<h3 id="PhilBiol">4.3 Philosophy of Biology</h3>

<p>
The philosophy of biology in the region has been developed in various
directions, from the most traditional topics in the area to more
innovative questions.</p>

<p>
The traditional topic of natural selection is treated in relation to
its explanatory power by Pablo Lorenzano in collaboration with the
Spanish philosopher Jos&eacute; D&iacute;ez (D&iacute;ez and Lorenzano
2013, 2015). Mario Casanueva (2011) proposes a structuralist
reconstruction of the mechanism of natural selection by means of graph
resources, and Santiago Ginnobili (2016) offers a metatheoretical
structuralist reconstruction of Darwin&rsquo;s theory with the purpose
of elucidating the concept of ecological fitness. Ginnobili also
approaches Darwinism by other perspectives: in collaboration with
Daniel Blanco, he compares Wallace&rsquo;s and Darwin&rsquo;s natural
selection theories (Ginnobili and Blanco 2019), he stresses that
Darwin confronted the idea of the objectivity of beauty (Ginnobili
2023a), and he analyzes how Darwin explained the origin of races
(Ginnobili 2023b) and modified previous functional biology (2022). In
turn, Gustavo Caponi (2013, in Spanish) studies the concepts of
function, fitness and adaptation in natural selection theory, and
explores how, with Darwin, the influence of living environment began
to be regarded as decisive for understanding the distribution,
configuration, and viability of living beings (Caponi 2022).</p>

<p>
Closely related to natural selection, the issue of evolution is
approached from very different perspectives. For instance, Guillermo
Folguera stresses the dependence of macroevolution on microevolution
even in the criticisms of the synthesis since the seventies (Folguera
and Lombardi 2012), Maurizio Esposito (2011) supplies examples of how
Darwinism was used and adapted in different contexts, and Francisco
Vergara Silva, in collaboration with two non-Latin American scholars,
asks to what extent the extended evolutionary synthesis expands the
explanatory power of traditional evolutionary theory (Baedke,
Fabregas&#8209;Tejeda, and Vergara&#8209;Silva 2020). The evolutionary
process is also analyzed by Ariel Roff&eacute; from different
perspectives: he considers drift as a constitutive factor of evolution
(Roff&eacute; 2019), he claims that a propensity account of fitness
solves the classical tautologicity issue (Roff&eacute; and Ginnobili
2019), and he argues that cladistic practice within the dynamic
framework presupposes the distinction between primary and secondary
homology (Roff&eacute; 2020). In turn, Sergio Mart&iacute;nez (2019)
argues for a sort of continuity from biology to social sciences,
according to which recent accounts of innovation in biology can be
extended to account for cultural innovation.</p>

<p>
However, the most extensive work on this issue has been developed by
Edna Su&aacute;rez-D&iacute;az who focused specifically on molecular
evolution. In this field, she studied the role played by the concept
of informational molecule and by the idea of molecular evolution of
informational molecules in differentiating molecular from classical
evolutionists and in the constitution of genomics
(Su&aacute;rez-D&iacute;az 2009, 2010). Despite stressing the
importance of the molecular experimental approach in evolutionary
biology (Su&aacute;rez-D&iacute;az and Barahona 1996;
Su&aacute;rez-D&iacute;az 2001), Su&aacute;rez-D&iacute;az
acknowledges the methodological and conceptual difficulties embedded
in the use of molecular evidence to elaborate molecular phylogenies
(Su&aacute;rez-D&iacute;az and Anaya-Mu&ntilde;oz 2008;
Su&aacute;rez-D&iacute;az 2014a), and emphasizes the generative nature
of experimentation (Su&aacute;rez-D&iacute;az 2013). In her recent
work, she points out that lateral gene transfer poses epistemic and
empirical challenges to the traditional reconstructions of
contemporary molecular phylogenetics (Estrada,
Su&aacute;rez-D&iacute;az, and Becerra 2022).</p>

<p>
Heredity, always linked with biological knowledge, has been the topic
of interest of Carlos L&oacute;pez-Beltr&aacute;n who shows the
transformation of the concept from playing a metaphorical role to
acquiring a narrative role (1994) and subsequently being conceived in
statistical terms (2006). More recently, L&oacute;pez-Beltr&aacute;n
has been concerned with genomics in relation to the concept of race.
In this field he has edited, with other researchers, a volume on race
mixture in Latin America (Wade, L&oacute;pez-Beltr&aacute;n, Restrepo,
and Ventura Santos 2014) and a special issue of the journal <em>Social
Studies of Science</em> (see the introduction in Wade,
L&oacute;pez-Beltr&aacute;n, Restrepo, and Ventura Santos 2015).</p>

<p>
By relating heredity with genetics, Esposito (2017) emphasizes the
longstanding relationships between the reductionist view of gene as
hereditary unit, the idea of information encoded in DNA, and the
prophecies about the power of controlling genetic information. From a
structuralist perspective, Lorenzano offers a metatheoretical
reconstruction of classical genetics (Balzer and Lorenzano 2000),
paying special attention to the Hardy-Weinberg&rsquo;s law within
population genetics (2014), and accounts for scientific explanation as
ampliative, specialized nomological embedding in the case of classical
genetics making use of Sneedian structuralism (Lorenzano an
D&iacute;ez 2022). Mario Casanueva (1997) explores the relationship
among the sexual theory of reproduction, Mendelian genetics, and
Mendel&rsquo;s hybridization theory. In turn, Juan Manuel Torres
(1997, 2002, 2006) focuses on the use of genetic tests in medical
practice, and Ana Barahona (2007) considers how different inheritance
issues can be represented by genetic maps. More recently and with
several collaborators, Jose Alonso-Pav&oacute;n and Barahona offer a
detailed map of genetics in M&eacute;xico (Alonso-Pav&oacute;n et al.
2001).</p>

<p>
Siobhan (formerly Fabrizzio) Guerrero Mc Manus examines some
methodological problems in biology: the rational selection of an
algorithm for phylogenetic inference (2009) and the limitations of
mechanistic explanations when dealing with developmental mechanisms
(2012). More recently, she has considered whether paleoanthropology is
merely a biological science or it requires attending to social,
cultural, and political issues (Mc Manus 2018). In turn, the issue of
causation is treated by Maximiliano Mart&iacute;nez in terms of the
concept of multi-level causation (Mart&iacute;nez and Moya 2011;
Mart&iacute;nez and Esposito 2014). The ideas of a multiplicity of
levels and of downward causation appear repeatedly in the works of
Charbel El-Hani (El-Hani and Pereira 1999; El-Hani and Emmeche 2000;
Queiroz and El-Hani 2006), with the purpose of advocating for property
and process emergence in biology. In his recent works, El-Hani has
focused on ethnobiology in order to contribute to developing a
&ldquo;philosophy of ethnobiology&rdquo; as an interdisciplinary field
devoted to exploring foundational issues in ethnobiology and expanding
the agenda of the philosophy of biology (Ludwig and El-Hani 2020, see
also Nieves Delgado, Ludwig, and El-Hani 2023), and has analyzed the
concept of &ldquo;ecosystem health&rdquo; and compares it with the
notions of health and malfunction in organisms (Sfara and El-Hani
2023).</p>

<p>
In collaboration with El-Hani, Jo&atilde;o Queiroz has developed
extensive work on the biosemiotic approach to biology (El-Hani,
Queiroz, and Stjernfelt 2010; Queiroz, Emmeche, Kull, and El-Hani
2011; Queiroz 2012; Queiroz, Stjernfelt, and El-Hani 2014), and its
relationship with genetic information (El-Hani, Queiroz, and Emmeche
2006). From a completely different viewpoint,
Su&aacute;rez-D&iacute;az (2007) discusses what she considers the
metaphor of information in molecular biology.</p>

<p>
Other non-classical but currently very relevant topics in life
sciences are also treated in the region, such as environmental matters
(Klier et al. 2017), ecology (Nunes-Neto, Moreno, and El-Hani 2014),
and evo-devo (Baedke and Mc Manus 2018).</p>

<p>
Finally, it is worth mentioning a recent trend that, in the confluence
among philosophy, anthropology, and biology, considers political
issues in biological research (Wade et al. 2014; Garc&iacute;a-Deister
and L&oacute;pez-Beltr&aacute;n 2015; Delgado 2018), studies genomic
variations in Latin America (Su&aacute;rez-D&iacute;az 2014b;
Anaya-Mu&ntilde;oz, Garc&iacute;a-Deister, and
Su&aacute;rez-D&iacute;az 2017), examines the relationship among
genetic research, nationalism, and the construction of collective
social identities (Kent et al. 2015), and explores the relationships
among homosexuality, homophobia, and biomedical sciences in the region
(Mc Manus 2014). In this context, Vivette Garc&iacute;a-Deister has
focused on the subtle relations between genetics and politics in Latin
America, by showing the dependence of diabetes not on genetics but on
socioeconomics (Garc&iacute;a-Deister and L&oacute;pez-Beltr&aacute;n
2015), by exploring the idea of national or regional genomic identity
(Vasques and Garc&iacute;a-Deister 2019), and by examining the
relationship between forensic genetics, Indigenous organization, and
human rights practice (Smith and Garc&iacute;a-Deister 2021). She also
considers the different ways in which engineering concepts and methods
have been applied in biology (Knuuttila and Garc&iacute;a Deister
2019) and analyzes the movement of living migrants&rsquo; bodies and
dead bodies as scientific objects and sociopolitical signposts for
sovereignty and identity (Garc&iacute;a-Deister and Smith 2020).</p>

<p>
Before closing this section, two sources of further information should
be noted. First, the book edited by Lorenzo Baravalle and Luciana
Zaterka (2020), which presents to English speaking readers a good
sample of research in the field of history and philosophy of biology
developed in Latin America. Second, the entry &ldquo;Philosophy of
Biology in Latin America&rdquo; (Lorenzano 2023b), which contains
information on the extensive material on the philosophy and the
history of biology in Spanish, as well as on studies on biological
issues in Latin American countries produced by foreign authors. .</p>

<h3 id="PhilFormScie">4.4 Philosophy of Formal Sciences</h3>

<p>
Sometimes very close to logic itself, the philosophy of logic has an
important presence in Latin American philosophy of science from
multiple perspectives.</p>

<p>
The logical treatment of contradiction attracted great interest,
mainly in the groups of Campinas and Buenos Aires, although with
different motivations. In Campinas, where one underlying interest was
the possibility of modeling contradictory information in scientific
practice, Newton da Costa focused on the mathematical concept of
&ldquo;pragmatic truth&rdquo; (Mikenberg, da Costa, and Chuaqui 1986)
with the purpose of showing that the logic of pragmatic truth is
paraconsistent (da Costa, Bueno, and French 1998). He also worked with
D&eacute;cio Krause in the application of paraconsistent logics to
physics (da Costa and Krause 2014, 2016). In turn, Walter Carnielli
and Marcelo Coniglio developed an approach in which the distinction
between logic and philosophy is not straightforward. On the
philosophical side, and following the path opened by da Costa, they
focused on the so-called &ldquo;logics of formal inconsistency&rdquo;,
a family of paraconsistent logics that can express the notion of
consistency within the object language (Carnielli, Coniglio, and
Marcos 2007). Carnielli also developed dialogical and epistemic
approaches to paraconsistency (Rahman and Carnielli 2000; Carnielli
and Rodrigues 2019). It is worth noting a book on contradiction and
inconsistency, compiled by Carnielli and the Polish logician Jacek
Malinowski (2018), which gathers contributions from various Latin
American authors.</p>

<p>
In the group led by Eduardo Barrio at Buenos Aires, works on
inconsistency were motivated by semantic reasons, in particular, the
treatment of paradoxes (Barrio 2010; Picollo 2012; Barrio and Picollo
2012; Rosenblatt and Gallovich 2022; Rosenblatt 2023). The members of
the group study non-transitivity as a solution of the paradox problem
(Barrio, Rosenblatt, and Tajer 2015), and considered substructural
approaches to paradoxes (Da R&eacute; and Rosenblatt 2018; Barrio,
Rosenblatt, and Tajer 2021; Rosenblatt 2021a; see also the special
issue of <em>Journal of Philosophical Logic</em> on substructural
logics and metainferences edited by Eduardo Barrio and Paul Egre
2022). They also propose and defend a new way of characterizing a
logic, that helps distinguishing the non-transitive logic ST from the
classical logic CL (Barrio, Pailos, and Szmuc 2020a). Some members of
the group were also interested in &ldquo;non-classical logic and
classical recapture&rdquo;, in the contexts of paraconsistent logic
(Teijeiro 2018, 2020a) and of logics of formal inconsistency (Tajer
2018, 2020); in particular, Lucas Rosenblatt analyzes the very concept
of classical recapture and faces the objections received by this
strategy from different perspectives (Rosenblatt 2021b, 2022; Fiore
and Rosenblatt 2023). Recently, Barrio and collaborators have begun to
focus specifically on paraconsistency in its different aspects
(Barrio, Pailos, and Szmuc 2017, 2018a, 2020b; Barrio and Da R&eacute;
2018; Barrio, Clerbout, and Rahman 2020), and Paula Teijeiro (2020b,
2022) has directed her attention to certain non-traditional logical
connectives.</p>

<p>
The strong contact between the groups of Campinas and Buenos Aires
resulted in the publication of two special issues of the <em>Logic
Journal of the IGPL</em> (Barrio and Carnielli 2020a, 2020b) devoted
to logics of formal inconsistency. The interest in paradoxes and
inconsistency also appeared in other authors of the region, such as
Andr&eacute;s Bobenrieth (1998).</p>

<p>
Topics related to non-extensionality, in particular modal logics and
Kripkean semantics, were also treated by some philosophers of logic in
Latin America (e.g., Mortari 2007; Marcos 2009;
Estrada-Gonz&aacute;lez 2013; Rosenblatt and Szmuc 2014). In
particular, Max Freund (2001, 2004, 2007, 2015) focused on modal
logics with sortal quantifiers and wrote a collaborative book on modal
logic (Cocchiarella and Freund 2008).</p>

<p>
The question of the coexistence of different logics was additionally
addressed by the groups in Buenos Aires and Campinas. Whereas Barrio
and collaborators discussed logical pluralism (Barrio, Pailos, and
Szmuc 2018b), Carnielli and Coniglio focused on the problems of
translations between logics (Carnielli, Coniglio, and
D&rsquo;Ottaviano 2009) and combinations of logics (Carnielli and
Coniglio 2007 [2016]). In M&eacute;xico, Luis Estrada-Gonz&aacute;lez
analyzed different aspects of contra-classical systems, which are
neither subsystems nor extensions of classical logic
(Estrada-Gonz&aacute;lez and Tan&uacute;s-Pimentel 2021;
Estrada-Gonz&aacute;lez 2023).</p>

<p>
More traditional problems related with the philosophy of logic have
also been treated by the philosophers of logic of the region; for
instance, the problem of truth (e.g. Barrio and
Rodr&iacute;guez-Pereyra 2015; Barrio and Da R&eacute; 2017) and the
meaning of connectives (Estrada-Gonz&aacute;lez 2011, 2017). In
particular, Mario G&oacute;mez-Torrente (1998, 2000, 2002, 2008, 2009,
2014) developed a longstanding work on the notion of logical truth,
truth preservation and the relationships among logical truth,
derivability and model-theoretic validity. More recently, he discusses
the notion of adequate formalization (G&oacute;mez-Torrente 2020) and
reviews the problem of logical constants (G&oacute;mez-Torrente
2021).</p>

<p>
In the group of Florianopolis, emerged under the influence of Newton
da Costa, Jonas Becker Arenhart analyzes the epistemic approach to
paraconsistency (Arenhart 2021) and discusses the idea of interpreting
paraconsistency (Arenhart 2022a). Following ideas of da Costa, he also
argues for the use of hypothetical models in logic (Arenhart 2022b)
and advocates for logical anti-exceptionalism, that is, the view that
logic is not special, but it is continuous with empirical science (da
Costa and Arenhart 2018; Arenhart 2022c). In turn, Arenhart and Krause
(2023) critically examine the concept of quasi truth in its
application to science.</p>

<p>
Although in the boundaries between logic and epistemology, the logic
of belief revision and the works of Carlos Alchourr&oacute;n
(Alchourr&oacute;n and Makinson 1981, 1982; Alchourr&oacute;n 1996)
cannot be forgotten: the AGM model (Alchourr&oacute;n,
G&auml;rdenfors, and Makinson 1985) is still the dominant theory of
belief revision (see entry
 <a href="../logic-belief-revision/">logic of belief revision</a>
 in this Encyclopedia). Andr&eacute;s P&aacute;ez (2006) uses the
theory of belief revision to supply a concept of explanation embodied
with pragmatic conditions. Closely related with this topic,
&ldquo;defeasible reasoning&rdquo; was extensively studied by Gustavo
Bodanza and Fernando Tohm&eacute; (2005, 2009; Bodanza, Tohm&eacute;,
and Simari 2016; Bodanza, Tohm&eacute;, and Auday 2017; see also
Bodanza 2002; Bodanza and Alessio 2017). More recently, Bodanza (2023)
developed a graph-theoretical tools to find properties that can be
applied both to the analysis of semantic paradoxes and to the
semantics of abstract defeasible argumentation, and proposes a
tableaux method that enables to calculate whether arguments are
accepted or rejected in accordance with the most common extension
semantics for argumentation frameworks (Bodanza and
Hern&aacute;ndez-Manfredini 2023).</p>

<p>
Tohm&eacute; also supplied a category-theoretic representation of
abduction (Tohm&eacute;, Caterina, and Gangle 2015), and analyzed
abduction in its application to economy (Crespo, Tohm&eacute;, and
Heymann 2010; Tohm&eacute; and Crespo 2013; Thom&eacute; 2022).
Abductive reasoning was also the main interest of Atocha Aliseda
(2003; Aliseda, Soler, and Nepomuceno 2009, 2023), who applied
abduction to medical diagnosis (Aliseda and Leonides 2013), proposed a
conditional logic to formalize abduction (Beirlaen and Aliseda 2014),
and argued for new tools to improve the logical approach to philosophy
of science (Aliseda 2022). She also published a book completely
devoted to abduction (Aliseda 2006), which not only discusses
conceptual and formal matters, but also pays special attention to the
epistemic applications of abductive reasoning.</p>

<p>
In the boundaries between logics and philosophy of science,
Mar&iacute;a del Rosario Mart&iacute;nez-Ordaz (2021, 2022a) considers
inconsistency toleration in sciences and the application of
paraconsistent logics in those cases.</p>

<p>
In the field of the philosophy of mathematics, Alfonso &Aacute;vila
(2006) has discussed in what sense the philosophy of mathematics is
different from mathematics and metamathematics, and
G&oacute;mez-Torrente (2015) has drawn conclusions about the essence
and identity of natural numbers. In turn, Eduardo N. Giovannini has
focused on the foundations of geometry (Giovannini 2016; Giovannini et
al. 2022) and has analyzed implicit definitions (Giovannini and
Schiemer 2019). Form a completely different perspective, Ulianov
Monta&ntilde;o (2014) proposes a naturalistic aesthetic theory that
accounts for aesthetic phenomena in mathematics.</p>

<h3 id="PhilCognScie">4.5 Philosophy of Cognitive Sciences</h3>

<p>
The philosophy of cognitive sciences is a very complex field, mainly
due to the difficulty to distinguish it from other areas such as
philosophy of mind, epistemology, linguistics, philosophy of action,
and logic.</p>

<p>
The traditional topic of consciousness has been treated in its
relationship to brain functions from a naturalized perspective by
Jos&eacute; Luis D&iacute;az (1995, 2000) and more recently by Miguel
Angel Sebasti&aacute;n (2014) on the basis of the neurophysiology of
dreams. In turn, Beatriz Sorrentino Marques and Osvaldo Pessoa (2017)
consider the role of consciousness in agent causation theories.</p>

<p>
Another traditional topic, perception, is addressed by Juan Carlos
Gonz&aacute;lez, who analyzes the process of perceptual recalibration
(Gonz&aacute;lez, Bach-y-Rita, and Haase 2005) and the case of
hallucinations (Gonz&aacute;lez 2010, 2016), and by Laura Dan&oacute;n
and Daniel Kalpokas (2017), who offer an explanation of the direct
perception of mental states of others. The problem of perception
continued to be Kalpokas&rsquo;s interest during the last years from a
propositional view of perception (2020a, 2020b, 2022a); in particular,
he argues that Brandom passes over a conception of perceptual
experience as a sort of contentful mental state (2019, 2022b).</p>

<p>
Juan Pablo Berm&uacute;dez focuses on mental actions, supplying an
account of skillful action that rejects both intellectualism and
anti-intellectualism (2017) and claiming that remembering is not
merely passive but must be viewed as a mental action and that even
mind-wandering can be intentional (Arango-Mu&ntilde;oz and
Berm&uacute;dez 2018, 2021). More recently, Berm&uacute;dez has
directed his attention to self-control, arguing that willpower
requires tactical skill, which detects willpower-demanding contexts,
selects context-appropriate tactics, and monitors their implementation
(Berm&uacute;dez 2021a, 2021b; Berm&uacute;dez et al. 2021), and he
has analyzed the difference between effort and the feeling of effort
(Berm&uacute;dez and Massin 2023).</p>

<p>
In collaboration with Berm&uacute;dez, Alejandro Rosas stresses the
cognitive and non-cognitive roots of shared intentionality (Rosas and
Berm&uacute;dez 2018) and the influence of cognitive dispositions on
weakness of will attribution (Rosas, Berm&uacute;dez, and
Guti&eacute;rrez 2018). In addition to his collaborative work with
Berm&uacute;dez, Rosas developed an extensive work on the evolution of
moral cognition and the cognitive roots of cooperation (2002, 2008a,
2021). In particular, he claims that altruism is selected both at the
individual and at the group levels (2008b) and proposes a unified
theory of human cooperation based on reciprocity (2010, 2012). In
turn, with colleagues coming from philosophy and from science, he has
contributed to the research on moral judgment with moral dilemmas
(Rosas and Koenigs 2014; Rosas, Viciana, Caviedes, and Arciniegas
2019).</p>

<p>
The phenomenon of abstraction has been considered by Sergio
Mart&iacute;nez from different perspectives: he claims that the
epistemic grounding of abstraction is related to the constraints on
the cognitive processes of specific abstractions (Mart&iacute;nez and
Huang 2011) and argues for the importance of the notions of
&ldquo;affordance&rdquo; and &ldquo;scaffolding&rdquo; as concepts
leading to the integration of different concepts into the right
abstraction (Estany and Mart&iacute;nez 2014).</p>

<p>
The problem of mistakes or slips, has captured the attention of
Santiago Amaya, who argues that the analysis of those common mistakes
illuminates aspects of human agency that tend to be overlooked when
the emphasis is placed on rationality (Amaya 2013, 2015; Amaya and
Doris 2015). More recently, he has focused on habits, arguing that
habits, just like beliefs, can guide intentional action (Amaya 2021).
</p>

<p>
An approach that has received much attention in the region is that of
embodied cognition and, particularly, enactivism (see Gonz&aacute;lez
2013; Hutto and Satne 2017; Mart&iacute;nez, Espa&ntilde;ol, and
P&eacute;rez 2018). For instance, Ignacio Avila analyzes bodily
awareness and its role in perceptual self-location (2014, 2017) and
considers certain enactive accounts of perception (2015). Adrian
Cussins (2012) discusses the role that the representation of the body
plays in cognition. In turn, Maria Eunice Quilici Gonz&aacute;lez asks
whether embodied cognition can be applied to artificial systems as
robots (Haselager and Gonz&aacute;lez 2007a).</p>

<p>
Axel Barcel&oacute; Aspeitia and Angeles Era&ntilde;a focused their
work mainly on the modularity of mind in order to adapt the idea of
domain specificity (Barcel&oacute;, Era&ntilde;a, and Stainton 2010)
and to compare the hypothesis of massive modularity to other views
about the structure of mind (Era&ntilde;a 2012). In this context,
Claudia Lorena Garc&iacute;a (2007) argues that the hypothesis of the
modularity of mind needs to be understood in terms of the evolutionary
biological concepts of variational independence (2007) and of
functional homology and functional variation (2010). More recently,
Garc&iacute;a proposes to categorize mental disorders as clusters of
interrelated disfunctions of cognitive capacities
(Salcedo-G&oacute;mez and Garc&iacute;a 2023).</p>

<p>
Metacognition is the topic that attracted the interest of Santiago
Arango-Mu&ntilde;oz, who distinguishes between the rationalizing level
and the controlling level in metacognition (2011) and appeals to the
concepts of metamemory and metacognitive feelings to address the
interactions between the mind and the world (2013). Furthermore, he
explores the nature of the so-called &ldquo;epistemic feelings&rdquo;
from a metacognitive perspective (2014, 2019).</p>

<p>
Cognitive functions are approached from an informational perspective
by M.E.Q. Gonz&aacute;lez, who analyzes mechanical models of
intelligence (2005) and of reasoning (Gonz&aacute;lez, Broens, and
D&rsquo;Ottaviano 2007; Haselager and Gonz&aacute;lez 2007b). From the
same informational approach, Sebasti&aacute;n and Marc Artiga (2020)
explore metarepresentation. Other formal perspectives are adopted to
verify the so-called cognitive task analysis (Laureano-Cruces and
Barcel&oacute;-Aspeitia 2002) and to analyze the agent&rsquo;s
resolution of conditional probability problems (Moro, Bodanza, and
Freidin 2011). In turn, Mariela Aguilera stresses the relevance of
pictorial and cartographical representation in cognition to express
normative contents (2019) and focuses on the inferential relations
between cartographic and linguistic representations (2021).</p>

<p>
From a completely different viewpoint, several authors in the region
prefer to understand cognitive phenomena in an analytical framework,
specifically in relation to language (e.g., Skidelsky 2013;
Garc&iacute;a-Ram&iacute;rez 2011; Garc&iacute;a-Ram&iacute;rez and
Shatz 2011), with affinity with research in philosophy of mind.</p>

<p>
The problem of attributing psychological states to non-human animals
is an issue that has sparked the interest of some researchers (see,
e.g., Crelier 2022). Laura Dan&oacute;n has paid great attention to
this topic, considering the possibility of intentionality (2019a),
normativity (2019b), propositional content (2022a), and conceptual
recombination (2022b) in non-human animals&rsquo; minds.</p>

<h3 id="PhilSociScie">4.6 Philosophy of Social Sciences</h3>

<p>
Certain methodological problems of social sciences have been addressed
by Diego R&iacute;os, who analyzed social explanation with mechanistic
and evolutionary models (2004; Kuchle and R&iacute;os 2015, 2022), and
studied the relationship between methodological individualism and
methodological holism (R&iacute;os 2005, 2009; R&iacute;os Pozzi
2007). Nevertheless, almost all of the philosophy of social sciences
in Latin America has been directed to theoretical issues in specific
sciences or particular problems of the region.</p>

<p>
With regard to the philosophy of economics, the foundations of the
theory of value have been studied (Garc&iacute;a de la Sienra 1988,
1989) and the autonomy and irreducibility of economics has been
discussed (Scarano 2012; G&oacute;mez 2012). More recently,
Jos&eacute; Carlos Ram&iacute;rez S&aacute;nchez and Adolfo
Garc&iacute;a de la Sienra (2020) analyze the impact of the dynamic
systems techniques on the recent development of neoclassical
economics.</p>

<p>
A field that attracts great interest is the philosophy of history.
El&iacute;as Palti recalls the evolution and crisis of the area
(2018), and distinguishes the so-called &ldquo;politico-intellectual
history&rdquo; from the old &ldquo;history of political ideas&rdquo;
(2010, 2014). More recently, Palti (2021) analyzes Deleuze&rsquo;s
interpretation of Foucault&rsquo;s idea of knowledge/power. Veronica
Tozzi (2012a, 2016, 2018), in turn, proposes an original pragmatist
approach to the philosophy of history, which appeals to Dewey&rsquo;s
notion of &ldquo;practical meaning&rdquo; in relation to the knowledge
of the past. Tozzi also focuses on the problem of the roles that
memory and testimony play in representing the recent past (2009,
2012b). In connection to these concepts, Esteban Lythgoe (2011, 2014)
analyzes how Paul Ricoeur articulates history, memory, and
testimony.</p>

<p>
Issues related to narrativism in history have also been studied. In
particular, Tozzi (2021, 2023) considers the epistemic value of
narrative explanation, and Mar&iacute;a In&eacute;s La Greca (2021)
finds a meaningful intersection between theory of history, gender
studies and narrativism. In turn, Natalia Taccetta (2021) explores
some artistic devices, in particular two films, which defy
history-writing conventions.</p>

<p>
Other topics involved in the philosophy of history have also been
considered: the historicity of the concept of subject (Palti 2004),
the ideas of progress (Ratto 2018), and of future (Belvedresi 2018).
Rosa Belvedresi (2019) also analyzes the concept of empathy in its
role in the epistemology of history. Mar&iacute;a In&eacute;s
Mudrovcic highlights the different types of consciousness of
temporality (2014, 2019) and analyzes the political self-understanding
of the present in terms of the past in contemporary Western societies
(2013). The impact of the phenomenon of globalization on
historiographical paradigms (Brauer 2018) and on the deformation of
ethical and political concepts (Rold&aacute;n 2018) are also examined.
In turn, the idea of Global History is considered by Belvedresi
(2012), who compares it with the concept of universal history, and by
Francisco Naishtat (2012) as a framework for the Marxist debate on
colonialism and modernization.</p>

<p>
At the crossroads between philosophy of politics and political
philosophy&mdash;if there is any difference between them&mdash;the
categories of equality and liberty (Hilb 1994), authority
(Oyarz&uacute;n 2012), identity politics (P&eacute;rez 2023), and
power (Oyarz&uacute;n 2017) have been analyzed. In this field,
Naishtat has developed extensive research aimed mainly at critically
evaluating phenomena on a global scale. For instance, he analyzes the
relationship between fragile sovereignties, global-intensive
governance apparatuses, and a horizon-less catastrophe-world (2010a),
and argues that the political dimension of the global is global
justice (2011). In turn, Naishtat stands in the context of recent
political events when he considers the possibility of peace and rights
transcending state frontiers in the light of the 1990s <em>Balkan</em>
wars (2000) and the displacement of the content of the terms
&ldquo;terror&rdquo; and &ldquo;terrorism&rdquo; after 9/11 towards a
meaning functional to globalization (2010b). More recently, he
explored the phenomenon of globalization from the perspective of the
controversy about the concept of time between Benjamin and Heidegger
(Naishtat 2018).</p>

<p>
Latin American themes are recurrent in the philosophy of social
sciences of the region. Palti has been very active in this field: he
studied the nineteenth century Latin American intellectual history in
the context of the thesis of the essential contestability of concepts
(2005), considered the limitations of the notion of &ldquo;misplaced
ideas&rdquo; by means of which Roberto Schwarz analyzed the dynamics
of ideas in Latin America (2006), and critically examined the radical
transformation in the ways of conceiving the process leading to the
break of colonial ties that linked Latin America with Spain (2009).
Other authors share this interest in regional problems, such as Pablo
Oyarz&uacute;n (2007), who focused on Latin American singularities,
Gustavo Leyva (2014), who considered how the democratic project was
reformulated and radicalized in Latin America over the last decades,
and Ambrosio Velasco G&oacute;mez (2015b), who proposes an original
thesis about the intellectual roots of Mexican independence.</p>

<p>
When Latin American themes are considered, the so-called Philosophy of
Liberation cannot be forgotten: a philosophical movement that emerged
in the late sixties in Argentina and spread through Latin America in
the following decades with authors such as Enrique Dussel, Leopoldo
Zea, Arturo Roig, Francisco Mir&oacute; Quesada, and Carlos Cullen,
among many others. Nevertheless, here the topic will not be treated
because a complete entry of the Encyclopedia is devoted to it (Eduardo
Mendieta,
 <a href="../liberation/">philosophy of liberation</a>).</p>
 
<h3 id="PhilTech">4.7 Philosophy of Technology</h3>

<p>
The philosophy of technology has attracted significant interest of
Latin American researchers working from very different perspectives,
whether ontological-epistemological or ethical-political. From a
general viewpoint, Ricardo G&oacute;mez (2010) offers a detailed
overview of the philosophical ideas about technology.</p>

<p>
Regarding the ontological status of technical artifacts and actions,
Diego Lawler critically analyzes the functional and intentional
theories about the nature of artifact kinks (Vega and Lawler 2014) and
proposes a praxeological approach to technological practices (Lawler
2018). In turn, Andr&eacute;s Vaccari directs criticisms to the
functionalist assumptions underlying the dual nature of technical
artifacts program (2013) and the extended cognition theory applied to
artifacts (2017), claiming that transhumanism has failed in its aim to
ground the transformation of the human condition on technology (2015).
In this context, Jorge Linares Salgado (2019, in Spanish) critically
analyzes the bioartifactual revolution that aims to biotechnically
reconfigure living organisms, emphasizing the ethical-philosophical
questions it raises. In turn, Sergio Mart&iacute;nez (2013) claims
that models of cultural evolution can be understood as modeling
cognitive processes embodied in the evolution of artifacts.</p>

<p>
More recently, Lawler and Vaccari have collaborated with other authors
to argue for an enactive conception of productive practices (Sandrone,
Vaccari, and Lawler 2022) and to point out the centrality of the
machine in the thought of Jacques Lafitte (Di Paolo, Lawler, and
Vaccari 2023). In turn, Vaccari (2020, 2022) has focused on the
concept of cosmotechnics, understood as the unification between the
cosmic order and the moral order through technical activities.</p>

<p>
The ontological status of artificial agents and artificial life was
addressed by Maria Gonz&aacute;lez and Osvaldo Pessoa (2008), who face
the problem of whether life and autonomy could in principle be
sustained with components other than carbon, and by Diego Parente
(2018), who considers the challenges that these cases pose to the
traditional dichotomy between natural/artificial. With regard to this
issue, Karina Pedace and coauthors (Pedace et al. 2019) argue that
humans are naturally transhuman and, so, urge to wake up from the
transhumanist dream. Pablo Rodr&iacute;guez and Javier Blanco (2017),
in turn, confront Gilbert Simondon&rsquo;s theory of individuation
with ideas coming from cybernetics.</p>

<p>
From an epistemological perspective, Myriam Altamirano Bustamante,
Adalberto de Hoyos, and Le&oacute;n Oliv&eacute; (2011) state that
much of the tacit knowledge involved in technology can be transmitted
as explicit knowledge through patents.</p>

<p>
The ethical and socio-political dimensions of technology are topics
that have received great attention in the region. For instance, Jorge
Linares Salgado (2018) analyzes the ethical and societal consequences
of the production of bio-artifacts derived from synthetic biology. A
more specific study is offered by Carlos Osorio Marulanda (2018), who
addresses the problems related with drinking water production,
especially in rural areas of Latin America, from the perspective of
science, technology, and society (STS) studies.</p>

<p>
In the area of STS studies, the extensive work of Hebe Vessuri
occupies a relevant place. In the boundaries between sociology and
philosophy, Vessuri has addressed general problems from a regional
point of view. For example, she considers how the current admission of
the underlying ontological complexity of the world influences both the
socio-cognitive and the institutional organization of disciplinary
knowledge, especially in developing countries (2000), and how science
and technology can respond to the particular needs of Latin American
societies (2003). Vessuri also discusses the world distribution of
scientists, engineers, and technologists and the movement of these
personnel from peripheral countries to central countries (de la Vega
and Vessuri 2008). More recently, Vessuri has been interested in the
problem of sustainability (Mercado, C&oacute;rdova, and Vessuri 2022)
and in the peculiarities of knowledge production in Latin America
(Vessuri 2019; Vessuri and Rodr&iacute;guez-Medina 2022). The readers
interested in STS studies in Latin America can turn to the article
&ldquo;Latin American science, technology, and society. A historical
and reflexive approach&rdquo; (Kreimer and Vessuri 2018), which
describes the development of STS in the region, its
institutionalization, and its spaces of interaction.</p>

<p>
Two themes that are very present in contemporary society, artificial
intelligence and big data, have also appeared in the philosophical
reflection of the region. Andr&eacute;s P&aacute;ez critically
examines the notion of explanation used in AI in general, and in the
theory of belief revision in particular (2009), and argues that the
search for explainable models and interpretable decisions in AI must
be reformulated in the broader context of a naturalistic account of
understanding in AI (2019). In turn, Mar&iacute;a del Rosario
Mart&iacute;nez-Ordaz addresses the question of whether there is
anything special about the ignorance involved in big data practices
(2022b), and argues that scientists can achieve some understanding of
both the products of big data implementation as well as of the target
phenomenon to which they are expected to refer (2023).</p>

<p>
Finally, two books in Spanish by Le&oacute;n Oliv&eacute; must be
recalled due to their impact in the Latin American community of
philosophers of science: whereas in the first (Oliv&eacute; 2000)
science and technology are considered on a par, the second book
(Oliv&eacute; 2007) deals specifically with the different facets of
technology. More recently, a book has been published, containig much
of the contemporary work on the philosophy of technology from the
Portuguese-Speaking Community. The book includes four collaborations
of Brazilian researchers: Ivan Domingues (2023), whose purpose is to
extend the current paradigms in the philosophy of technology, Alberto
Cupani (2023), who analyzes the difference between scientific and
technological knowledge, Renato Dagnino (2023), who proposes the
concept of solidary technoscience, which is particularly relevant for
Latin American countries, and Hugh Lacey and Pablo Mariconda (2023),
who criticize the predominance of commercially oriented technoscience
and advocate for a new model for the interaction between technological
activities and values. In turn, Mar&iacute;a Antonia Gonz&aacute;lez
Valerio, in collaboration with the Slovenian author Polona Tratnik,
published a book devoted to biotechnological art from a philosophical
viewpoint (Gonz&aacute;lez Valerio and Tratnik 2023).</p>

<h3 id="OtheTopi">4.8 Other Topics</h3>

<p>
Other topics, not easily included in the traditional philosophies of
particular sciences, have also been addressed in Latin America.</p>

<p>
What is now known as philosophy of information has been an interest of
Olimpia Lombardi and her research group from different perspectives.
The meaning of the term &ldquo;information&rdquo; is elucidated from a
general viewpoint (Lombardi 2004), paying particular attention to
Shannon information (Lombardi 2005; Lombardi, Holik, and Vanni 2016a),
and arguing for a pluralistic interpretation of the concept (Lombardi,
Fortin, and Vanni 2015). By adopting a critical perspective regarding
Christopher Timpson&rsquo;s deflationary view of information
(Lombardi, Fortin, and L&oacute;pez 2016), it is argued that there is
no qualitative difference between Shannon and quantum information
besides the difference in the way in which they are encoded (Lombardi,
Holik, and Vanni 2016b). In turn, an interpretational account of
quantum measurement is offered (Lombardi, Fortin, and L&oacute;pez
2015). On the basis of this critical work, Lombardi and Cristian
L&oacute;pez (2018) have elucidated the concept of information as used
in Giulio Tononi&rsquo;s Integrated Information Theory of
Consciousness, and have proposed a manipulation-based interpretation
of communicational information (L&oacute;pez and Lombardi 2019).</p>

<p>
The philosophy of science as a resource for science education is a
topic that has acquired an increasing interest in Latin America during
the last decades. In this field, two authors have developed intensive
work. Agust&iacute;n Ad&uacute;riz-Bravo addressed the use of
well-known episodes from the history of science, such as the
formulation of the pendulum law by Galileo (2004) and the discovery of
radium by the Curies (Ad&uacute;riz-Bravo and Izquierdo-Aymerich 2009)
for science education. Moreover, he applied the cognitive model of
science (Izquierdo-Aymerich and Ad&uacute;riz-Bravo 2003;
Ad&uacute;riz-Bravo and Izquierdo-Aymerich 2005) and the semantic view
of scientific theories (Ad&uacute;riz-Bravo 2011, 2013) both to the
practice of science teaching and to research on science education. He
also appealed to the so called &ldquo;Nature of Science&rdquo; view of
science for the education of science teachers (Ad&uacute;riz-Bravo
2007, 2014) and to abduction for science education
(Ad&uacute;riz-Bravo and Sans Pinillos 2022). On the basis of those
theoretical foundations, Ad&uacute;riz-Bravo focuses on the philosophy
of chemistry as a resource for the didactics of chemistry (Erduran,
Ad&uacute;riz-Bravo, and Mamlok Naaman 2007; Izquierdo-Aymerich and
Ad&uacute;riz-Bravo 2009; Ad&uacute;riz-Bravo, Merino, and
Izquierdo-Aymerich 2012; Sar&#305;ta&#351;, &Ouml;zcan, and
Ad&uacute;riz-Bravo 2021). Recently, he has expanded his network of
international collaborations to provide a framework for
epistemological discussion on integrated STEM education
(Ortiz-Revilla, Ad&uacute;riz-Bravo, and Greca 2020), to study how
school scientific argumentation is enriched by digital technologies
(Romano, Occelli, and Ad&uacute;riz-Bravo 2021), and to show how
narratives on epidemics can be used as tools for science teaching in
secondary schools (Revel Chion and Ad&uacute;riz-Bravo 2022)</p>

<p>
Much of the interest of Charbel El-Hani has been centered on the
philosophy of biology for the didactics of biology. He advocates for a
theory-centered approach to the concept of life (2008) and considers
the advantages of the dialogue between the students&rsquo;
ethnobiological knowledge and biology school knowledge (Baptista and
El-Hani 2009). He also appeals to the works of Mendel and Darwin for
teaching genetics and evolution (Bizzo and El-Hani 2009; El-Hani 2015)
and analyzes the different concepts of gene that often overlap in
biology education (Dos Santos, Joaquim, and El-Hani 2012; Meyer,
Bomfim, and El-Hani 2013; Gericke, Hagberg, dos Santos, Joaquim, and
El-Hani 2014). More recently, he has discussed how the conceptual
content for biology high school curricula should be selected (de
Carvalho, El-Hani, and Nunes-Neto 2020) and proposes a model for
teaching the nature of science in the context of biological education
(In&ecirc;z, de Lacerda Brito, and El-Hani 2023). Beyond the specific
field of biology, El-Hani accounts for the different ways in which
individuals and societies represent concepts (Aguiar Jr, Sevian, and
El-Hani 2018), discusses how to deal with the relations between
different cultural perspectives in classrooms (Moreira-dos-Santos and
El-Hani 2017), and advocates for understanding as one of the major
goals of science education (Ferreira, El-Hani, and da Silva Filho
2016).</p>

<h2 id="ConcRema">5. Concluding Remarks</h2>

<p>
After reviewing the development of philosophy of science in Latin
America since its emergence in the mid-twentieth century, it can be
said that there are some distinctive features in the different
countries. But in the last decades, especially given the widespread
use of the Internet and digital libraries by the mid-1990s, a growing
intercommunication and collaboration can be verified as well as the
tendency to form an academic community with an important international
presence, which, at the same time, has certain characteristics of its
own. Among the common features, the following deserve to be
mentioned.</p>

<ol type="a">

<li>In general, in Latin American countries the philosophy of science
began to be cultivated in the mid-twentieth century in those academic
circles that were favorable to analytic philosophy, understood in a
broad sense. The so-called &ldquo;philosophical analysis&rdquo;, more
than a school or doctrinal body, represented in Latin America an
alternative way of doing philosophy: in this trend, the methodological
demands of conceptual elucidation and argumentative rigor supported a
reaction against the metaphysical, speculative, or dogmatic traditions
that predominated in the 1940s. Thus, analytical philosophy favored
the focus on problems posed in the fields of logic, science, and
language (without restricting the analysis of the latter to ordinary
language). Based on this common root, since the 1960s philosophy of
science has acquired a place of its own in most countries of the
region.</li>

<li>Although the &ldquo;Americanist&rdquo; concern (understood as the
search for a philosophy of the region, with its own identity) did not
prevail in philosophy of science of Latin America, the constant and
growing exchange between Latin American philosophers of science has
had the result of generating lines of research that integrate the
concerns for the social problems afflicting the countries of the
region and the role that science and technology can play in its
solution. Thus, from the 1990s, a triple movement was generated:
orientation towards practical issues, openness to other philosophical
traditions&mdash;different from the analytic tradition&mdash;, and a
direct connection between the main Latin American nuclei where
philosophy of science is developed.</li>

<li>At the turn of the century, a vigorous growth of the philosophy of
particular sciences can be observed, especially the philosophy of
physics and biology, and more recently the philosophy of cognitive
sciences. The philosophy of chemistry&mdash;a field that had been
ignored all over the world until 1980&mdash;has only recently begun to
be cultivated in countries such as Argentina and Mexico. In contrast,
in philosophy of the social sciences, Latin America shows an unequal
growth compared to the philosophy of the natural sciences. Despite
this, it can be said that a sustained effort is being made to promote
areas such as the philosophy of psychology, sociology, and economics.
Furthermore, the philosophy of formal sciences has advanced
significantly.</li>

<li>Regarding the philosophy of technology, it received very little
attention until the end of the last century. However, the frequent
interaction with the Spanish philosophers of technology, through their
participation in specialized meetings and their collaboration in
graduate programs, has favored the cultivation of this research axis
in close connection with the critical reflection on the relationships
between technology and the economic, social, and environmental
problems afflicting the region.</li>

<li>Regarding general philosophy of science, its development shows a
remarkable diversification in Latin America. In a relatively short
period of time&mdash;which started in the late 1980s&mdash;there has
been a growing expansion of problems, approaches, and lines of
research. Even the discussion of great classical problems, such as
rationality and realism, is carried out from alternative perspectives,
many of which have recovered the naturalist approach of classical
pragmatists, which in the 1960s gained a new impetus under the
so-called &ldquo;Historicist turn&rdquo;. On the other hand, this
strong tendency to develop a naturalized philosophy of science has
been accompanied by the defense of markedly pluralist positions, both
in the methodological as well as the epistemological and ontological
fields. All of this points to a conception of philosophical work that,
without neglecting argumentative rigor and conceptual elucidation,
deals with and worries about the problems of its context and
historical moment. In the philosophy of science, this has been
reflected in a growing awareness of the need to rethink the
relationships among science, technology, and society, along with its
ethical, political, economic, environmental, and gender
dimensions.</li>

<li>One aspect worth emphasizing is the gender distribution of
researchers in the region. While the philosophy of science in Latin
America was originally exclusively masculine, the situation began to
change slowly but steadily since the last decade of the past century.
As the years of publication progress, a greater presence of women in
the production of the area is observed. Although we are still far from
an equitable representation in terms of gender, the trend allows us to
expect that in the near future women and other gender identities will
have a much greater participation in the production of philosophy of
science in the region.</li>

<li>By way of conclusion, it should be noted that, in contrast to the
way in which philosophy of science has developed in the Anglo-Saxon
sphere, works in Latin America have moved much more rapidly from the
merely &ldquo;academic&rdquo; stage, where discussions revolve around
what other colleagues (classical or contemporary) have proposed, to
the stage of critical reflection on the problems of broader social
environment in which scientific activity takes place. However, it
should also be noted that this expansion of horizons has not
negatively affected the research on the central problems of the
discipline (logical, semantic, methodological, pragmatic,
epistemological, and ontological), which continues to be the core of
the curriculum of the specialized degree programs, as well as of the
research centers where philosophy of science is developed.</li>
</ol>

<p>
Finally, it is worth stressing that the area has strongly progressed
despite the many obstacles that philosophical research faces in the
region; the erratic political situation and cyclical economic crisis
in Latin American countries influence research policies, placing
scholars in unstable and uncertain positions. Nevertheless, regardless
of the difficulties, at present a new generation of young philosophers
of science allows us to foresee that the philosophy of science
produced in Latin America will continue to grow in quantity and
quality, increasing its already considerable international
presence.</p>
</div>

